HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED OF A POSSIBLE HAZMAT SPILL ON MAY 17, 1996 AT 0305L.  ONE BOX OF ID ID800 WAS CRUSHED BY A FORKLIFT.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED IN THE DISPOSAL AREA AWAITING DISPOSITION BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPT.

RESPONDER NOTIFIED OF A FUMING PACKAGE ON THE DOCK. RESPONDER DONNED PPE AND RETRIEVED PACKAGE. THERE WAS NO 5-PART AND NO LEAKING ONLY SLIGHT FUMES. THE PACKAGE WAS HANDLED AS AN UNLABELED PACKAGE ACCORDING TO THE DECISION TREE. BECAUSE THE PACKAGE HAD A PH OF 3 IT WAS THEN HANDLE AS A CORROSIVE. WHEN PACKAGE WAS OPENED THERE WERE OVERWHELMING FUMES SO PACKAGE WAS PROCESSED WITH SCBA ACCORDING TO THE DECISION TREE AND THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET.

I RESPONDED TO SPILL.  THE CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEETS WERE USED. SODIUM BICARBONITE WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL.  PH TAPE WAS USED AND A READING BETWEEN 6-9 WAS RECEIVED.  THE EMPTY CONTAINER WAS BAGGED AND TAKEN TO THE DMP FOR DISPOSAL.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR UNIT WAS WEST BOUND ON I-80 APPROACHING A CONSTRUCTION ZONE. THE SIGNAGE WAS NOT CLEAR AND TRAFFIC QUICKLY NARROWED CAUSING OUR UNIT TO HIT AN ARROW SIGN AND BLOWING THE LEFT FRONT STEER TIRE. WHEN THIS HAPPENED, THE UNIT JERKED TO THE LEFT, WENT ACROSS THE MEDIAN, ACROSS THE EAST BOUND LANES AND UPSET ON A BANK ON AN EXIT RAMP AFTER HITTING A LIGHT POLE. AN EAST BOUND CAR VEERED RT AND HIT THE LIGHT POST RESULTING IN A FATALITY AND 2 INJURIES. THESE WERE NOT CAUSED BY THE HAZARDOUS WASTE. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED AND ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP. THE UTAH EPA APPROVED THE CLEAN UP.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT DELIVERY SITE, STARTED TO PUMP OFF LOAD, WHEN A FITTING BLEW OFF THE PIPE HE WAS PUMPING INTO, WELL CONTAINED. BFI ASSUMED RESPONSIBILITY AS IT WAS THEIR EQUIPMENT FAILURE.

ON WEDNESDAY, JUNE 05, 1996, AT 3:15 P.M., APPROXIMATELY THREE GALLONS OF WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID SPILLED OUTSIDE OF CONTAINMENT FROM A TANKER DOME LID THAT WAS NOT SECURELY FASTENED. THE TRUCK HAD BEEN SAMPLED IN BAY 3 OF OUR UNLOADING PAD. THE DOME LID WAS NOT SECURELY FASTENED AFTER THE SAMPLE HAD BEEN TAKEN. THE TANKER WAS THEN MOVED TO MAKE ROOM FOR ANOTHER TRUCK. IT WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTICED THAT FUEL WAS SPILLING FROM THE DOME LID AND THE TRUCK WAS STOPPED. THE SPILL COVERED ABOUT A SEVEN SQUARE FOOT AREA. THE DOME LID WAS IMMEDIATELY SECURED AND THE SIDES OF THE TRUCK WERE WIPED DOWN. A SMALL LOADER WAS USED TO COLLECT THE CONTAIMINATED SOIL AND GRAVEL WHICH WAS PLACED INTO THREE DRUMS THAT WILL BE SENT OFF-SITE FOR DISPOSAL. CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED JUST AFTER 3:30 P.M. ** EMERGENCY COORDINATES IMPLEMENTED THE CONTINGENCY PLAN IMMEDIATELY, ASSISTING THE SITUATION AND MAKING NOTIFICATIONS TO THE PROPER AGENCIES. NO ONE WAS INJURED AND PROTECTION OF HUMAN HEALTH AND THE ENVIRONMENT WERE THE TOP PRIORITIES OF THE PLANT TEAM AS THEY HANDLED THE INCIDENT. DETAILS OF THE FUEL ANALYSIS AND THE MANIFEST OF THE LOAD IN QUESTION ARE ATTACHED. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, CONCERNS OR COMMENTS, PLEASE CALL.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM WASTEX INDUSTRIES, INC. LOCATED AT 28 S HANOVER STREET IN POTTSTOWN, PA TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCES RECOVERY. INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS OF CONECTICUT, INC. LOCATED AT 51 BRODERICK ROAD IN BRISTOL, CT IN ORDER TO TRANSFER.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRANFER OPERATIONS, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEIDATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASED, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPPEDY DRI AND PLACED THE CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE WASTE MANAGEMENT.  FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  FACILILTY PERSONNEL DISCOVERED THAT THE RELEASE WAS CAUSED BY A DEFECTIVE GASKET USED TO CREATE A SEAL BETWEEN TE LID AND THE CONTAINER.

CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE, INC.  ROUTINELY CONSTRUCTS FIELD SERVICE ACTIVITIES WHICH INCLUDES THE OPERATION OF DIESEL POWERED EQUIPMENT.  IN ORDER TO CONDUCT THESE ACTIVITIES IT IS SOMETIMES NECESSARY TO PROVIDE ADDITIONAL FUEL FOR THE EQUIPMENT THAT IS USED IN THE FIELD. AS SUCH SMALL AMOUNTS OF DIESEL FUEL ARE TRANSPORTED TO VARIOUS JOB SITES FOR USE.  ON THE DATE IN QUESTION, THE DRIVER OF A PICK UP TRUCK THAT WAS TRANSPORTING A CONTAINER HAD TIPPED OVER CAUSING THE TOP CLOSURE TO OPEN. THIS RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF LESS THAN 10 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL TO THE ASPHALT ROADWAY.

column168: UNIT SOUTH BOUND ON NARROW (PAVED) COUNTY ROAD, TRAVELING AT APPROXIMATELY 50 MPH.  DRIVER SWERVED TO AVOID STRIKING AN ANTELOPE WHICH HAD ENTERED THE ROADWAY.  PUP TRAILER (TANK) WHIPPED AND PUP RAN OFF LEFT SIDE OF ROAD.  WHILE RE-ENTERING ROAD, LIQUID IN THE TANK SLOSHED TO RIGHT, BACK TO LEFT CAUSING PUP TO ROLE ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE, BREAKING LOOSE FROM MAIN TRAILER, ROLLING ONTO ITS TOP, THAN OVER ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE WHERE IT CAME TO REST ON LEFT SHOULDER OF ROAD.  WHILE SKIDDING ON ITS TOP, THE MAIN HATCH WAS TORN OFF AND ENTIRE CONTENTS OF PUP TRAILER WAS EMPTIED OUT ONTO THE GROUND.  SPEED LIMITS FOR TRUCKS OPERATING ON THIS HIGHWAY HAVE BEEN SIGNIFICANTLY REDUCED.  NO DESIGN CHANGE IS ANTICIPATED AS THIS IS A ISOLATED INCIDENT.  THE INTEGRITY OF THE TANK WAS NOT THREATENED AND HELD SUBSTANTIALLY.

JIMMY THEN REALIZED THAT HE HAD A LEAKING VALVE CAUSING THIS TO BUILD PRESSURE IN HIS HOSE, SO HE DECIDED TO RELIEVE THE PRESSURE FROM HIS TRAILER BY OPENING THE VENT LINE AND ALSO BY HOOKING HIS HOSE TO THE HEADER AND OPENING BOTH VALVES. DOCK MAN ACCIDENTLY DROPPED THE CARTON ON THE FLOOR WHILE IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSFERRING THE CARTON FROM THE PALLET TO A DOCK CART.  THE IMPACT OF THE CARTON HITTING THE CONCRETE DOCK FLOOR CAUSED BOTH GLASS BOTTLES TO BREAK INSIDE THE CARTON IN SPITE OF THE VERMICULITE PACKING. DAMAGED CARTON TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  DOCK PERSONNEL MUST HANDLE CARTONS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WHEN REQUIRED TO BE HANDLED BY HAND WITH GREAT CARE IN ORDER TO PREVENT ACCIDENTAL DROPPAGE.

PUMPING OFF LOAD AT CHEMCENTRAL FOR ABOUT 1/2 HOUR WHEN THE PUMP PACKING LET LOOSE.  PRODUCT STARTED RUNNING OUT FROM AROUND THE PTO SHAFT ON THE PUMP AND ONTO THE CEMENT UNLOADING PAD.  APPROXIMATELLY 10 TO 20 GALLONS RAN OUT BEFORE HE GOT THE TRAILER LINE SHUT OFF.  THE CONSIGNEE PUT OIL DRY ON THE SPILLED PRODUCT, SWEPT IT UP AND PUT INTO A DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: WHILE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING GASOLINE INTO UNDERGROUND SERVICE STATION STORAGE TANKS, A DEFECTIVE SEAL ALLOWED PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE UNLOADING FITTING.  THE LEAK RESULTED IN A PRODUCT SPILL OF ONE (1) GALLON OF GASOLINE.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE FLOW OF PRODUCT AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT WITH A SPILL KIT.  THE DEFECTIVE SEAL WAS REPAIRED AND THE DRIVER FINISHED UNLOADING THE GASOLINE.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED AND ALL CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE TERMINAL FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: OUR DRIVER NOTICED PAINT LEAKING FROM HIS TRAILER AT THE AMOCO TRUCK STOP IN BISMARCK, ND.  HE CALLED THE BISMARCK POLICE.  THEY ATTENDED WITH THE BISMARCK FIRE DEPARTMENT.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR (HOBB'S WAS HIRED TO CLEAN UP THE TRAILER AND PLACED THE LEAKING DRUM INTO AN OVERPACKED DRUM.  THE OVERPACK AND CONTENTS WERE DELIVERED WITH THE LOAD TO THE CONSIGNEE AT BLACK EAGLE, MT.

THE DRIVER DISCOVERED DRIPPING MATERIAL FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANKER WHILE STOPPED IN SNOWSHOE, PA.  HE CONTAINED THE DRIP BY TAPING ABSORBANT PADS TO THE TANKER.  HE THEN DROVE THE TANKER TO A SECURE AREA APPROXIMATELY 13 MILES AWAY, EAGLE TOWING & RECOVERY, INC.  IN WINGATE, PA.  EAGLE TOWING & RECOVERY, INC. IS LICENSED BY THE PENNSYLVANIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENAL RESOURCES ("PADER") FOR HAZARDOUS WASTE EMERGENCY RESPONSE.  THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TANKER AT THIS SITE.  CONTAMINATED TANKER AND TANKER PADS WERE RETURNED TO THE TRANSPORTER'S HOME TERMINAL.  SEE ITEMS 4 & 5 FOR FULL NAME AND ADDRESS.) ACTIONS TO BE TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS INCLUDE AN INCREASED FREQUENCY OF TANKER CLEANINGS.

UPON DELIVERY AT THE DESIGNATED TREATMENT FACILITY, THE DRIVER DISCOVERED DRIPPING MATERIAL FROM THE TAILGATE OF THE TOLL-OFF.  THE DRIVER WAS DIRECTED TO AN AREA WITH CONCRETE CONTAINMENT.  FLOOR DRY WAS USED TO ABSORB THE MATERIAL THAT DRIPPED.  THE CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS ADDED TO THE ORIGINAL ROLL-OFF BOX.  ACTIONS TO BE TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS INCLUDE INFORMING THE CUSTOMER OF THE PROBLEM AND INSURING ROLL-OFF BOXES DO NOT CONTAIN FREE LIQUID PRIOR TO TRANSPORTAITON.

WE WERE UNLOADING A SULFURIC ACID RAILCAR INTO OUR STORAGE TANK WHEN THE RAILCAR EMPTIED OUT, OUR STORAGE TANK WAS TO FULL TO HANDLE THE AIR PRESSURE FROM THE RAILCAR.  IT BLEW EMPTY CAUSING THE SULFURIC TO COME OUT OF THE VENT ON THE TOP OF THE TANK.  WE LATER FOUND THAT OUR GUAGE WAS SLIGHTLY OFF.  OUR PERSONNEL SHUT OFF THE AIR AND PRODUCT VALVE STOPPING THE FLOW.  THEY THEN SWITCHED TO ANOTHER TANK SO THE AIR PRESSURE IN THE RAIL CAR COULD FINISH BLOWING OFF.  WE WILL REPLACE THE GAUGE AND IN THE FUTURE WHEN THE GAUGE READS ZERO WE WILL PUMP THE TANK TO ANOTHER JUST TO DOUBLE CHECK THAT THE TANK REALLY IS EMPTY.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM THE MAYO FOUNDATION LOCATED AT 200 1ST ST IN ROCHESTER, MN TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO, IL.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT THE STANDARD TRUCK STOP LOCATED ON ROUTE 52 NORTH IN CANNON FALLS, MN TO CONDUCT A ROUTINE LOAD AND TIRE CHECK.  DURING THE LOAD CHECK, THE DRIVER DISCOVERED A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL DRIPPING FROM THE BACK OF THE VAN TRAILER.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SPREAD SPEEDY DRI OVER THE RELEASED MATERIAL AND PLACED A CONTAINMENT PAIL UNDER THE LEAK.  HE THEN CONTACTED HIS HOME DISPATCHER FOR ASSISTANCE.  AT THIS TIME, CLEAN HARBOR'S CORPORATE COMPLIANCE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED OF THE EVENT AND INITIATED CALLS TO THE APPLICABLE STATE AGENCIES IN MINNESOTA.  WHILE THE STATE WAS BEING NOTIFIED, THE DRIVER'S DISPATCHER CONTACTED A LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY TO PROVIDE ASSISTANCE IN RESPONDING TO THE RELEASE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW IDENTIFIED THAT 1 X 55 GALLON DRUM HAD DEVELOPED A SMALL PINHOLE LEAK ON THE TOP OF THE DRUM WHICH ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES OF MATERIAL TO ESCAPE FROM THE DRUM ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER.  A SMALL PORTION OF THIS MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE TRUCK ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA OF THE TRUCK STOP. THE RESPONSE CREW ENTERED THE TRAILER AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  IN ADDITION, 1 X 5 GALLON CONTAINER OF CONTAMINATED SPEEDI DRY WAS GENERATED IN CONJUNCTION WITH REMOVAL OF SPEEDI DRY FROM THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA AS WELL AS FROM THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER.  ALL WASTE MATERIAL GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT. ******* PRIOR TO DEPARTING FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO DEFICIENCIES WERE NOTED. THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE DAMAGED AND/OR LEAKING.

A PALLET HAD FALLEN FROM A TRUCK WHILE LOADING IT ONTO A FORKLIFT. MACHINERY WAS LEANING ON A DRUM OF RADIOACTIVE HAZMAT.  AMERIJET CONTACTED MIAMI DADE AND THE HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM OF A POSSIBLE HAZMAT SPILL. HAZMAT TEAM DISCOVERED 1 OF 3 CANS OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL HAD BEEN PUNCTURED AND OPENED A SEAM.  THE BREECHED DRUM OF MATERIAL WAS DETERMINED BY THE TEAM TO NOT BE LEAKING.

ON JUNE 24, 1996, I WAS NOTIFIED BY A WHEELING REPRESENTATIVE THAT INDUSTRIAL CHEMICAL CORP. HAD CALLED REQUESTING ASSISTANCE WITH A TANK CAR AT THEIR FACILITY WHICH WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING.  TANK CAR PPGX 3079. I SPOKE WITH JIM CAMAGLIA ON THE PHONE AND TOLD HIM THAT I WOULD RESPOND AND ASSIST IN HIS PROBLEM.  UPON ARRIVAL AT INDUSTRIAL CHEMICAL WE INSPECTED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS A LEAK FROM THE TANK ITSELF.  THE LOCATION OF THE LEAK WAS UNDETERMINED DUE TO THE TANK BEING LINED AND JACKETED.  PRODUCT WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE JACKET AT THE A END STUB SEAL OPENING OF THE JACKET AND AN EXTERNAL HEATER COIL OPENING OF THE JACKET. INDUSTRIAL CHEMICAL HAD ALREADY SPOKEN TO PPG AND DETERMINED THAT THE BEST SOLUTION WOULD BE TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT TO A RESIDUE TANK CAR PPGX 3220 WHICH WAS ALSO LOCATED ON THEIR PROPERTY.  WLE RESPOTTED THE LEAKING TANK CAR ADJACENT THE RESIDUE TANK CAR TO ASSIST IN TRANSLOADING. RECEPTACLES WERE PLACED UNDER CAR TO CATCH LEAKING PRODUCT AND PRODUCT WAS TRANSLOADED.  TANK CAR WILL BE RETURNED TO PPG INDUSTRIES, NATRIUM, WEST VIRGINIA FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.

FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED IN THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  DRIVERS AND FACILITY PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT CONTAINERS AS THEY ARE LOADED AND WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING OR DAMAGED.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH IN ORDER TO TRANSFER THE CONTAINERS ONTO A SECOND TRANSPORT VEHICLE FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORTATION.  DURING THE TRANSFER OPERATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 QUART OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP LID OF FOUR OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY. THIS MATERIAL WAS THEN PLACED IN THE DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.   AN INSPECTION OF THE 4 LEAKING DRUMS IDENTIFIED THAT THE GASKETS USED BETWEEN THE DRUM AND THE TOP CLOSURE WERE DEFECTIVE.  BECAUSE OF THIS, A COMPLETE SEAL WAS NOT ACHIEVED WHEN THE DRUMS WERE INITIALLY CLOSED.  PRIOR TO CONTINUING TRANSPORT, THE RESPONSE CREW REPLACED THE DEFECTIVE GASKETS AND RE-SEALED THE DRUMS.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  DRIVERS AND FACILITY PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT CONTAINERS AS THEY ARE LOADED AND WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING OR DAMAGED.

PLEASE NOTE THAT THIS WAS NOT A PACKAGE FAILURE.  ATTACHED SHEET WILL IDENTIFY CIRCUMSTANCES SURROUNDING RELEASE.  A CARGO TANK OPERATED BY CLEAN HARBORS AT 45 ALDRIN ROAD IN PLYMOUTH, MA IN ORDER TO LOAD AND TRANSPORT A SHIPMENT OF FERRIC CHLORIDE SOLUTION TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY AVENUE IN CLEVELAND, OH.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE LOADING SITE, THE CREW CONDUCTING THE LOADING OPERATION INITIATED THE LOADING PROCEDURES WHICH INCLUDED SETTING UP AN AIR COMPRESSOR AND A DOUBLE DIAPHRAGM PUMP TO CONDUCT THE PRODUCT TRANSFER. ONCE THE TRANSFER EQUIPMENT WAS IN PLACE, THE INDIVIDUAL LOADING THE TANK STARTED THE PUMP AND IMMEDIATELY NOTICED PRODUCT ESCAPING FROM TWO SEAMS ON THE PUMP ONTO THE ASPHALT LOADING AREA.  THE PUMP WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN AND SPEEDI DRY AND LIME WAS USED TO CONTAIN AND ABSORB APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL THAT WAS RELEASED FROM THE PUMP.  ONCE THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED, A CALL WAS PLACED TO THE DRIVERS HOME DISPATCHER REQUESTING ASSISTANCE WITH THE CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES. AN EMPLOYEE WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE WITH A REPLACEMENT PUMP AND ADDITIONAL CLEAN UP SUPPLIES.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE CREW CONTAINERIZED THE SPILL DEBRIS AND REPLACED THE DEFECTIVE PUMP WITH A NEW UNIT.  TWO 5 GALLON CONTAINERS OF SPEEDY DRI CONTAMINATED WITH FERRIC CHLORIDE WERE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, EACH PUMP USED TO ASSIST WITH THE LOADING OF A TANK VEHICLE WILL BE TESTED AND INSPECTED PRIOR TO DISPATCH TO INSURE IT IS IN PROPER WORKING ORDER.  IN ADDITION, POLYETHYLENE SHEETING WILL BE PLACED UNDER THE PUMP TO MINIMIZE GROUND CONTAMINATION IN THE EVENT A PUMP FAILS IN THE FUTURE.

A VANDAL GAINED ACCESS TO SHOP AREA, HOOKED UP A 90% ELBOW AND A 15 LENGTH OF 3" HOSE TO REAR VALVE ON TANK TRAILER #SKT 745.  OPENED TWO VALVES TO ALLOW OIL TO FLOW DOWN THE BACKLOT INTO THE SHOP AREA AND AROUND THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE BUILDING TO 11TH ST.  WHEN THE OIL GOT TO 11TH ST.  A PASSING MOTORIST CALLED IN TO DISPATCH THE FIRE DEPT.  THE FIRE DEPT. DIKED THE OIL TO KEEP FROM ENTERING THE SEWER, FIRE DEPT. CALLED DAVE STEPHAN WHO IN TURN CALLED ME.  WHEN I ARRIVED ONSCENE I OPENED ALL DOORS & TURNED ON THE EXHAUST FAN TO DISIPATE ANY FUMES, THEN STARTED TWO TRUCKS AND PUMPED OIL FROM INSIDE SHOP AREA AND OUT IN THE STREET, AFTER ALL LIQUID WAS PUMPING AND MORE HELP ARRIVED GROUND CLEANUP BEGAN IMMEDIATEY.  THE MISSING LOCK ON THE REAR VALVE WAS REPLACED.

AT 1030 AM 6-9-96 NOTIFIED BY HB&T CARMAN OF CAR LEAKING VAPORS INTO THE AIR.  CARMAN BOTTS HAD HEARD HISSING SOUND AND SMELLED STRANGE ODOR WHILE INSPECTING TRAIN.  WHEN HE REALIZED CAR WAS LEAKING FUMES HE EXITED THE AREA AND WARNED SWITCH CREW COMING THAT WAY OF THE INCIDENT.  CARMAN BOTTS RODE SWITCH ENGINE TO THE NORTH END OF THE YARD AND WAS EXPERIENCING BURNING SENSATION OF EYES AND FACE, SOME DIZZINESS.  YARDMASTER, TRAINMASTER WERE NOTIFIED.  TRAINMASTER NOTIFIED CHEMTREC, SHIPPER, AND HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE HFD AMBULANCE DECONTAMINATED CARMAN BOTTS AND TRANSPORTED HIM TO THE HOSPITAL AS PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE.  AT HOSPITAL HE WAS SCRUBBED, DECONTAMINATED, GIVEN EYE DROPS, BLOOD TESTS, CHEST X-RAYS AND ALL RESULTS WERE NORMAL.  CARMAN BOTTS WAS RELEASED & ADVISED TO FOLLOW UP WITH COMPANY PHYSICIAN.  IN SHORT, HFD SECURED THE AREA, SPRAYED CAR WITH WATER TO REDUCE TEMPERATURE, AWAITING TRANSFER TRUCKS ORDERED BY SHIPPER.  TRUCKS ARRIVED 8:00PM AND ENTIRE CONTENTS OF TANK CAR WAS TRANSFERRED AND COMPLETE AT 1:30 AM.  BNSF TRAIN CREW OF 3 MEMBERS WHO WERE HELD IN SHANT SOME 2000 FT. AWAY FOR A SHORT TIME COMPLAINED OF INHALING VAPORS.  THE BNSF RAILROAD ADVISED THAT THE THREE EMPLOYEES SAW THEIR PERSONAL PHYSICIANS AFTER COMPLETING THEIR TOUR OF DUTY ON THE MORNING OF THE 10TH.  REPORTS ARE THAT ALL THREE TREATED AND RELEASED, AND HAVE WORKED SINCE WITHOUT ANY COMPLAINTS.  CAR CELX 5131 WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION AFTER TRANSLOADING COMPLETE.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: APPROXIMATLEY 04:30 ON JUNE 18, 1996 OUR DRIVER WAS PROCEEDING WEST ON RT. 422 ON A STRAIGHT LEVEL STRETCH OF HIGHWAY.  FOR AN UNKNOWN REASON, THE TRUCK DRIFTED TO THE RIGHT, STRUCK THE GUARDRAILS FOR ABOUT 300 FEET THEN LEFT THE ROADWAY TO THE RIGHT.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER APPARENTLY ROLLED OVER AND CAME TO REST AT THE BOTTOM OF A FORTY FOOT EMBANKMENT.  DURING THE OVERTURN INCIDENT, THE TRAILER BUCKELED, BURST AND WAS TORN OPEN.  THE TRUCK CARRIED 7501 GALLONS OF LOW SULFUR DIESEL FUEL.  AFTER THE TRAILER CAME TO REST, APPROXIMATELY 1200 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL REMAINDED IN THE TRAILER COMPARTMENTS AND WAS ABLE TO BE RECOVERED.  THE BALANCE WAS CONTAINED WITHIN AN AREA APPROXIMATELY 50FT BY 100FT.  WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO CONTAIN THE SPILL AND BEGIN CLEANUP PROCEDURES.  THE INCIDENT WAS INVESTIGATED BY THE PENNSYLVANIA STATE POLICE.  THE PENNSYLVANIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION WAS ADVISED OF THE SPILL AND SEVERAL REPRESENTATIVES WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.

column168: RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED AT 0325L ON JUNE 12, 1996, OF A POSSIBLE HAZMAT SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL IT WAS NOTED THAT A FOUL ODOR WAS COMING FROM A HUT. THE HUT WAS BROKEN DOWN AND THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE LOCATED.  DRUMS AND CLEANUP MATERIAL WERE PLACED IN A DISPOSAL DRUM IN THE DISPOSAL AREA AWAITING DISPOSITION BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPT.

SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED AT 0110L ON JUNE 26, 1996, OF A POSSIBLE HAZMAT SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL IT WAS NOTED THAT ONE 5 GALLON DRUM WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM A BROKEN SEAL IN THE LID. SHIPMENT WAS CONTAINERIZED AND AND PLACED IN THE DISPOSAL AREA AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM THE ENVIRONMENTAL ARRAIRS DEPARTMENT.
DURING THE LOADING OF A RAILROAD TANK CAR, THE HOLDING STRAP WHICH SECURED THE HOSE BROKE.  THIS ALLOWED THE HOSE TO PULL OUT OF THE HATCH.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1415 HOURS IN BUCKEYE YARD, EMPLOYEES NOTICED PRODUCT ON THE SIDE OF SCMX 2892 NEAR THE SAFETY VALVE.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR ASSISTANCE.  SHELL'S REPRESENTATIVE FOUND THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE MINUS THE SPRING.  HE REPLACED THE VALVE AND RELEASED THE CAR AT 1810 ON JUNE 11TH.

AFTER RECEIVING THE OK TO UNLOAD, DRIVER PRESSURIZED TRAILER AND STARTED TO UNLOAD CARGO TANK.  THEIR SUPERVISOR INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVER TO SHUT DOWN.  A LEAK DEVELOPED BETWEEN FLOORS IN PIPE.  REPAIR WAS MADE BY PIPEFITTERS AND SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY CONSIGNEE'S PERSONNEL.
CENTRAL TRANSPORT CONNECTED HOSE, TURNED ON PUMP, AND HOSE STARTED LEAKING AT CONNECTION.  TURNED OFF PUMP, UNHOOKED HOSE, AND FOUND A GASKET MISSING.

ONE FIVE GALLON CONTAINER WAS SITTING ON THE ABF DOCK WHEN THE SUPERVISOR ON DUTY NOTICED THE CARTON LEAKING.  HE INVESTIGATED THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK, BUT NO ONE ON THE DOCK SAW WHAT HAPPENED.  IT APPEARS THAT THE CONTAINER WAS HIT WITH THE BLADE OF A FORKLIFT.  THE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP WITH WOOD CHIPS AND PLACED INTO A PLASTIC CONTAINER.  THE CLEANUP WAS DILUTED WITH EQUAL AMOUNTS OF WATER.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY. INSTRUCTIONS WERE RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.  THE PRODUCT WAS DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL REGULATIONS.  THE REMAINING FREIGHT WAS FORWARDED PER INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.
AT TIME OF UNLOADING, FOTKLIFT PUNCTURED EDGE OF BAGS CAUSING MINIMAL LOSS.  CUSTOMER ACEPTED ENTIRE SHIPMENT.

RELEASES THE FREIGHT, MR. BROOKS WILL BE ASKED TO PICK UP THE PACKAGE IN A NON-COMMERICAL VEHICLE.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: DURING THE OFFLOAD THE BOX DEVELOPED A LEAK.  THE BOX WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT, PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD PENDING A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  APPROXIMATELY FOUR HOURS LATER, THE PHL RAMP CALLED AND ADVISED THAT THEY HAD A SPILL IN THE AFT BULK OF FEDEX AIRCRAFT IN 487 FE. THE MATERIAL WAS FROM THE SAME SHIPMENT THAT HAD SPILLED IN MEM.  THAT FREIGHT WAS CLEANED UP AND HELD AT THE PHL RAMP FOR THE FAA ALSO.  I SPOKE TO PATTY PAUSCH AT THE PHL CASFO & TERRY BURGESS AT THE BNA CASFU.  THE FREIGHT HAS BEEN INSPECTED BY BOTH FAAS.  THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN NOTIFIED. NONE OF THE BOXES HAD ANY MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATOR TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  THIS SHIPMENT IS UNDECLARED.

DURING THE SORT THE BOX WAS DROPPED UPSIDE DOWN CRUSHING THE INNER CONTAINER AND DAMAGING THE CLOSURE.  MOST OF THE MATERIAL ESCAPED WHICH WAS ULTIMATELY RECOVERED.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND BOX WERE BOTH PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND FAXED A COPY OF THE DECLARATION TO THE FEDEX MEMPHIS HUB OPERATION.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED, INSPECTED THE FREIGHT, AND RELEASED IT.  THE FREIGHT HAS SINCE BEEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THIS SHIPMENT IS UNDECLARED.

column168: DURING AM SORT OPERATION, SHIPMENT IS REPORTED TO HAVE AN ODOR. INVESTIGATION REVEALS A 4L CAN OF METHANOL/METHYL ACETATE AND SEVERL CANS OF PAINT AND PAINT-TYPE SUBSTANCES AND INK.  THERE IS A MSDS FOR THE INK, THAT INDICATES A FLASH POINT OF 125-130F (SEE ATTACHED).  NONE OF THE FOUR PACKAGES ARE MARKED LABELED OR CERTIFIED AS DANGEROUS GOODS. EWR/FAA-CAFSO IS NOTIFIED.  PACKAGE HELD AT LOCATION PENDING COMPLETION OF FAA INVESTIGATION.

DURING THE SORT THE BOX BEGAN LEAKING.  EMPLOYEE PAUL WHITAKER GOT SOME OF THE LEAKING CHLOROFORM INTO AN OPEN CUT HE HAD ON HIS HAND.  HE IMMEDIATELY WASH FOR 15 MINUTES, FELT NO ILL EFFECTS, AND REFUSED MEDICAL ATTENTION.  UPON OPENING THE BOX WE FOUND SEVERAL BOTTLES OF MATERIAL THAT HAD BEEN HEAPED INTO THE PLASTIC BAG.  MANY OF THE BOTTLES DID NOT MEET OR WERE IN DIRECT OPPOSITION TO THE ORIENTATION ARROWS ON THE BOX.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED DUE TO THIS PACKAGING DISCREPANCY.  THE FAA HAS INSPECTED THE FREIGHT AND RELEASED IT.  THE BOX WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM, THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN NOTIFIED, AND WE ARE WAITING FOR DISPOSITION FROM THEM.

BRUCE STEIN HAD BEEN AT A CONVENTION, WAS OFFERED SEVERAL SAMPLES, DIDN'T WANT TO CARRY THE HOME AND WENT TO A KINKO'S IN DES MOINES, IA.  THERE  HE WAS HELD BY A KINKOS EMPLOYEE WHO SAW THAT MR. STEIN WAS PUTTING AEROSOL CANS INTO HIS BOX.  THE EMPLOYEE ALLEGEDLY DID NOT WARN OR TRY TO DISCOURAGE HIM FROM SHIPPING AEROSOL CANS.  THE FREIGHT WAS FLOWN FROM DSM TO IND WHERE THE MATERIAL LEAKED.  THE SHIPPER & FAA HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED. THE FAA HAS INSPECTED & RELEASED THE FREIGHT.  THE SHIPPER & FAA HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED.  THE FAA HAS INSPECTED & RELEASED THE FREIGHT.  THE SHIPPER WILL FAX SHIPPING PAPERS.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS. OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THAT THE CONTENTS CONTAINED A MATERIAL THAT WAS REGULATED.  THIS SHIPMENT IS UNDECLARED.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED ON 6/18/96 THE FIRST TIME.  WE FOUND ODORS WITH THE FREIGHT, BAGGED THE JERRICANS, PUT THEM IN SALVAGE DRUMS, AND RETURNED THEM TO THE SHIPPER.  THE SHIPPER TOOK THE BAGGED JERRICANS OUT OF THE SALVAGE DRUMS AND PLACED THEM IN PLAIN OVERPACKS AND RE-TENDERED THEM TO FEDEX.  ONCE AGAIN THE FREIGHT ARRIVED IN MEMPHIS EMMITTING STRONG ODORS. THE BOXES THIS TIME WERE PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUMS AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  CONJECTURE:  THE SHIPPER DID NOTHING TO ALLEVIATE THE POTENTIAL FOR STRONG ODORS UPON THE FIRST RETURN.  WE BELIEVE THIS WAS A WONTON ACT AND SEVERLY PUT OUR OPERATION AT-RISK.  I HAVE DISCUSSED THE MATTER WITH THE SHIPPER AND ADVISED THAT IF A SIMILAR TYPE SCENARIO WERE TO OCCUR AGAIN, FEDEX WOULD HAVE NO CHOICE BUT TO REFUSE ALL FUTURE SHIPMENTS.  THE SHIPPER GAVE VERBAL ASSURANCES THAT THIS WOULD NOT BE REPEATED.

ALL FREIGHT WILL BE HELD UNTIL THE FAA INSPECTS & RELEASES IT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0430 ON THE 29TH OF JUNE, 1996. A CTI EMPLOYEE WAS IN THE PROCESS OF MOVING A TRACTOR-TRAILER WHEN A TURN CAUSED A ROLL-OFF BIN TO RELEASE FROM THE TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS IN THE MIDDLE OF OUR MAINTENANCE PROCESS WHEN THE ACCIDENT OCCURED. THE CABLE (REAR) WHICH SECURE THE LOAD, WAS BEING REPLACED. CTI EMPLOYEE WAS NOT AWARE THE REAR CABLE WAS MISSING AND ATTEMPTED TO MOVE THE TRAILER. CHEMICAL TRANSPORT INC. RESPONDED TO THE SPILL (CTI YARD) AND RELOADED MATERIAL INTO ANOTHER BIN. CTI HAS AN ESTABLISHED POLICY WHICH ADDRESSES THE SECURING ROLL-OFF BINS PRIOR TO MOVING THE TRACTOR TRAILER. IT IS MY OPINION THIS INCIDENT WAS DUE TO MISCOMMUNICATION AND CAN BE ADDRESSED WITH PROPER RETRAINING OF OUR PERSONNEL.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1400 HOURS ON JUNE 27TH IN SELKIRK YARD, CAR INSPECTORS NOTED A STRONG GLUE-LIKE ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR ACFX 72804. KNOWLEDGEABLE CONRAIL EMPLOYEES INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE OPEN AND VENTING.  THE TEAM ACTUATED THE VALVE SEVERAL TIMES AND IT RESEALED.  THE CAR WAS RETURNED TO TRANSPORTATION.  MONSANTO WAS REQUESTED TO INSPECT THE VALVE UPON DELIVERY TO THEIR PLANT.

DRIVER HAD STOPPED AT A CONVENIENCE STORE/TRUCK STOP TO MAKE AFTERNOON CHECK-IN CALL.  WHEN RETURNING TO TRUCK AND TRAILER TO PROCEED TO UNLOAD, DRIVER FOUND PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE VENTING PRESSURE.  WHILE RELIEF VALVE WAS VENTING, APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS EXPELLED FROM THE TANK TRAILER.  EXCESS PRESSURE WAS FOUND TO BE FROM A REACTION OF THE MATERIAL IN THE TANK TRAILER.  CONTAINMENT OF THE AREA WAS STARTED IMMEDIATELY WITH THE HELP OF SAFETY KLEEN PERSONNEL.  MATERIALS WAS FOUND TO BE ON THE GRAVEL PARKING LOT, ROADWAY, SOME BUILDINGS AND A GRASSY AREA. ****** CLEAN-UP WAS DONE BY AN EPA EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR. CLEAN-UP WAS DONE BY REMOVING SOIL AND GRAVEL FROM PARKING LOT AND PLACED INTO ROLL-OFF BIN FOR DISPOSAL.   GRASS WAS MOWED AND BAGGED, BUILDINGS CLEANED, VEHICLES WERE WASHED AND CLEANED AT SAFETY KLEEN.  PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WAS TESTED AND FOUND TO BE IN PROPER WORKING ORDER, WITH VALVE OPENING AT THE PROPER PRESSURE.  PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON CARGO TANK TRAILER FUNCTIONED AS DESIGNED, THUS PREVENTING A MORE SERIOUS INCIDENT.

A SPILL OCCURRED DURING A ROUTINE DELIVERY OF JET FUEL TO THE SAN DIEGO AIRPORT.  A DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO UNLOAD THE CONTENT OF A TRUCK INTO TWO UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS.  THE TRUCK DRIVER DID NOT CLOSELY ATTEND THE UNLOADING OF PRODUCT AND OVERFILLED THE FIRST TANK WHICH RESULTED IN A SPILL OF TEN (10) GALLONS.  IN ADDITION, THE TANK OVERFILL HIGH ALARM AND SHUTDOWN DID NOT FUNCTION.  WHEN THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THE OVERFILL, THE DRIVER HALTED PRODUCT FLOW TO THE TANK AND CLEANED UP PRODUCT WITH ABSORBENT SPILL PADS.  ALL SPILL PADS WERE SENT TO THE TERMINAL FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED AND RETRAINED ON PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES.  THE HIGH LEVEL ALARM AND SHUTDOWNS ON ALL THE TANKS AT THIS FACILITY WERE INSPECTED AND REPAIRED AS REQUIRED.

column168: SEVENTEEN CAPACITORS CONTAINING PCBs WERE PREPARED FOR SHIPMENT BY PACKAGING IN THE USUAL MANNER AS HAD BEEN PERFORMED FOR THE PAST 5 YEARS. THIS PREPARATION CONSISTED OF PLACING 12 CAPACITORS IN A STRONG WOOD BOX DESIGNED TO HOLD A MAXIMUM OF 12 CAPACITORS AND PLACING THE OTHER 5 CAPACITORS IN A SIMILARLY SIZED AND CONSTRUCTED WOODEN BOX ALONG WITH BLOCKING AND BRACING TO PREVENT MOVEMENT WITHIN THE BOX.  PRIOR TO PLACEMENT WITHIN THE BOX, EACH CAPACITOR WAS MARKED WITH A HAZARDOUS WASTE "LABLE", A PCB MARK, AN RQ MARK, AND A CLASS 9 LABEL.  THE OUTSIDE OF EACH CRATE WAS MARKED AND LABELED IN A SIMILAR MANNER.  EACH BOX WAS LOADED ONTO THE BACK OF A FLAT BED TRAILER WITHIN A CONTAINMENT PAN WHICH RAN THE LENGTH OF THE TRUCK AND BRACED WITH A NYLON STRAP TO PREVENT MOVEMENT. FIVE OTHER STEEL 55 GALLON CAPACITY DRUMS WERE LOADED AT THE SAME PICK-UP LOCATION (BOISE, ID), THESE ITEMS BEING PLACED AT THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER AND BLOCKED TO PREVENT MOVEMENT.  THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE ERICKSON, INC YARD IN SALT LAKE CITY, UTAH AND THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE ROLLINS FACILITY AT ARAGONITE, UT.  AT NO TIME DURING INSPECTIONS IN TRANSIT OR IN THE ERICKSON YARD WAS THERE ANY EVIDENCE OF A SPILL OR LEAK. FIFTEEN MINUTES AFTER ARRIVING AT THE DISPOSAL FACILITY, THE SPILL WAS DISCOVERED.  UPON DISCOVERY, THE MATERIAL WAS UNLOADED AND PROCESSED (I.E., INCINERATED) AND THE SPILL CLEANED UP, THIS MATERIAL ALSO BEING INCINERATED.  IT IS BELIVED BY ERICKSON THAT DUE TO THE PLACEMENT OF THE BOXES ON THE END OF THE TRAILER, WHICH WAS BASICALLY EMPTY, THE BOXES WERE SUBJECTED TO EXCESSIVE FORCE WHICH CAUSED THE BLOCKING AND BRACING WITHIN THE WOODEN BOX CONTAINING 5 CAPACITORS TO LOOSEN.  DURING THE MOVEMENT BETWEEN THE ERICKSON YARD AND THE ROLLINS FACILITY SIMILAR FORCES CAUSED THE BLOCKING AND BRACING TO FAIL.  UPON STOPPING AT THE FACILITY, ONE OR MORE OF THE CAPACITORS DISLODGED STRIKING THE BOX, SEVERING THE INSULATOR FROM THE CAPACITOR CAUSING THE CAPACITOR TO DISCHARGE ITS CONTENTS.  THE CONTAINMENT PAN SEAL FAILED (POSSIBLY DUE TO SHIFTING OF THE BOXES DUE TO THE SAME FORCES WHICH CAUSED THE BRACING IN THE BOXES TO FAIL.  ERICKSON HAS INSTRUCTED ITS DRIVERS TO PLACE LADINGS AS CLOSE TO THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER AS POSSIBLE.  THIS SHOULD MINIMIZED THE FORCES TO WHICH THE LADINGS ARE SUBJECTED.  ERICKSON HAS OBTAINED AND IS TRAINING ITS DRIVERS THROUGH AN INSTRUCTIONAL VIDEO, "SECURITY THE LOAD", PREPARED BY THE TRANSPORTATION LOSS PREVENTION AND SECURITY COUNCIL OF THE AMERICAN TRUCKING ASSOCIATION, IN APPROPRIATE LOADING, BLOCKING AND BRACING FUNDAMENTALS.

column168: OUR DRIVER STOPPED AT THE FLYING J TRUCK STOP IN MATTHEWS, MO.  WHEN HE NOTICED CHEMICALS LEAKING FROM FRONT OF TRAILER.  IT WAS JUST A SLOW DRIP. DELTA SERVICES OF SIKESTON, MO. WAS CALLED OUT.  THEY TOOK THE LOAD TO SIKESTON, MO.  TO THEIR PLACE AND UNLOADED THE DRUMS.  THEY KEPT 4 AND CLEANED THE TRAILER AND RELOADED THE REMAINDER BACK TO THE TRAILER.  DELTA TOOK CARE OF THE DISPOSAL OF THE BAD DRUMS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND VERY LITTLE SPILLAGE.  WHEN THE LOAD WAS LOADED THEY PUT 2 DEAD PALLETS IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  THE BARRELS BEHIND THEM ON THE 2ND ROW OF PALLETS TIPPED FORWARD CAUSING THEM TO RUB ON THE FRONT PALLETS AND DEVELOPE LEAKES IN THE DRUMS.

ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS & SERVICE CONDUCTED THE CLEAN-UP AND FINISHED ON JUNE 20TH.

ONE PERSON, RACHEL KACZOUKA, HAD GOTTEN SOME TYLENE IN EYE. cOMPLAINED OF REDNESS AND IRRITATION.  WENT TO DOCTORS FOR TREATMENT AND RETURNED TO WORK.

DURING TRANSPORT OF THE LOAD, THE LOAD SHIFTED CAUSING THE 5-GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINER TO OVERTURN ON ITS SIDE.  A PIPE CAME TO REST ON THE CONTAINER.  THE PRESSURE FROM THE PIPE CAUSED THE TOP TO BE PINCHED AND MATERIAL TO LEAK FROM THE CONTAINER.  WHEN THE MATERIAL BEGAN LEAKING, IT LEAKED OUT OF THE INTERIOR OF THE TRUCK.  SEVERAL VEHICLES TRAVELING BEHIND THE TRAILER WERE SPLASHED WITH THE CONTENTS OF THE PAIL.  AFTER THESE DRIVERS GOT THE ATTENTION OF THE CF MOTOR FREIGHT DRIVER, HE STOPPED AT THE NEAREST EXIT.  THIS EXIT WAS 152 ON I-40 WEST.  THE TRAILER WAS TRAVELING WEST ON I-40 FROM NASHVILLE TO MEMPHIS.  THE DRIVER UPON EXITING THE INTERSTATE STOPPED AT RUBY'S RESTAURANT AND MOTEL.  FERGUSON HARBOUR INCORPORATED OF HENDERSONVILLE, TENNESSEE WAS CONTACTED AND ASKED TO RESPOND TO THE SITUATION.  THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS PLACED IN A 55-GALLON DRUM WHICH HAD A DRUM LINER IN PLACE.  STAY DRY MATERIAL, ABSORBENT PADS, CARDBOARD, AND PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT WERE PLACED IN THE DRUM.  IN ADDITION, GRAVEL FROM THE PARKING LOT AT RUBY'S RESTAURANT WAS REMOVED AND PLACED IN THE 55-GALLON DRUM WITH THE OTHER MATERIAL.  SOIL WHICH WAS IMPACTED WAS LIMITED TO THE UPPER 2 TO 3 INCHES OF PACKED GRAVEL.  IT WAS REPORTED BY THE GOVERNMENT INSPECTOR ON-SITE THAT 1 GALLON IMPACTED THE GROUND SURFACE.  THERE WAS NO IMPACT TO SURFACE WATER OR GROUNDWATER, OR TO SENSITIVE RECEPTORS.

column168: YARD CREW OBSERVED NOISE AND VAPOR COMING FROM THE TOP OF CPDX 180074. THE TRAINMASTER INVESTIGATED AND CONFIRMED THAT VAPOR WAS BEING RELEASED FROM THE VALVE HOUSING AREA OF THE DOME.  THE AREA HAZMAT MGR RESPONDED AND FOUND THAT THE PACKING GLAND OF THE GAUGING DEVICE WAS LOOSE AND ALLOWING VAPOR TO BE RELEASED.  HE ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE PACKING GLAND, BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL.  THE SHIPPER SENT PERSONNEL FROM RESCAR TO ASSIST. ALL FURTHER ATTEMPTS TO SECURE THE LEAK MECHANICALLY WERE UNSUCCESSFUL. THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR WAS TRANSLOADED INTO TRUCKS AND THE CAR WAS PURGED WITH NITROGEN TO REMOVE THE AMMONIA AND REDUCE PRESSURE IN THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS THEN SENT TO A REPAIR SHOP TO HAVE THE SUBJECT VALVE REPLACED.

column168: DRUM WAS RECEIVED FROM TOWNE AIR FREIGHT AT APROXIMATELY 2030. DOCK PERSONNEL DO NOT REMEMBER UNLOADING; MAY HAVE BEEN PUSHED OFF TRUCK BY DRIVER INTO SECOND DAY FREIGHT STAGED NEAR THE DOCK DOOR. DRUM WAS INSPECTED AND REJECTED AT APPROXIMATELY 2130 FOR REASONS NOTED ON ATTACHED CHECKLIST. AT APPROXIMATELY 2230, DOCK PERSONNEL ADVISED ME BOTTOM OF DRUM WAS BULGING. I PUSHED THE DRUM AND IT SOUNDED LIKE ICE IN WATER. A STICKER ON DRUM STATED CONTENTS SHOULD BE KEPT AT 40 DEGREES OR LESS. I WAS CONCERNED DRUM WOULD BURST FROM PRESSURE BUILDING INSIDE DUE TO WHAT I THOUGHT WAS MELTING ICE. I INSTRUCTED THE DOCK PERSONNEL TO MOVE DRUM OUTSIDE INTO FIELD IN BACK OF BUILDING. AFTER CONSULTING EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK FOR POTENTIAL HAZARDS, I CALLED BUREAU OF DANGEROUS GOODS FOR FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS. RUSS BOWEN ADVISED ME TO CALL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 2300 AND WE WERE ADVISED TO EVACUATE THE BUILDING. FIRE DEPARTMENT INSPECTED DRUM. YOUNG'S ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP, INC. WAS CALLED. AT APPROXIMATELY 0130, DRUM WAS VENTED. AT APPROXIMATELY 0140, WE WERE ALLOWED BACK IN BUILDING. DRUM WAS REMOVED BY YOUNG'S LATER IN MORNING BEFORE START OF OPERATIONS.

DRIVER WAS TRAVELING DOWN THE ROAD AND HE WAS TOLD AT A STOP LIGHT BY A DRIVER THAT THERE WAS SOMETHING LEAKING FROM UNDER THE TRAILER. DRIVER PULLED INTO A CITGO STATION DOWN THE ROAD TO SEE WHAT IT WAS. THE DIESEL LINE HAD BROKE OFF ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRAILER. THIS CAUSED A SPILL OF 60 GALLONS OF DIESEL. THE SPILL WAS CONTROLLED BY THE DRIVER UNTIL FIRE DEPT. ARRIVED AND TOOK OVER THE CLEAN-UP. DRIVER WAS NOT AT FAULT. MISSION WILL SEE THAT EQUIPMENT IS PROMPTLY FIXED.

1 EACH 55 GALLON POLY DRUM OF SULFURIC ACID WAS LOADED ON FLOOR OF TRAILER AND WAS SECURED TO SIDE OF TRAILER WITH TIE DOWN STRAPS. DURING TRANSPORTATIN A HAND TRUCK USED TO MOVE FREIGHT SLID ONTO THE BOTTOM OF DRUM. THE HAND TRUCK PUNCTURED THE DRUM AT THE BOTTOM. APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS LEAKED FROM THE DRUM. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO STOP THE LEAK BY LAYING THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE. THE FIRE DEPT AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM RESPONDED, AND THE FIRE DEPT ASSUMED COMMAND TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. THEY ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 PM AND THE SITE WAS CLEANED. THE SPILL WAS CONFINED TO THE TRAILER AND APPROXIMATELY 35 FT OF THE CONSIGNEES LOADING DOCK AREA.

DRIVER WAS TRAVELLING SOUTHBOUND ON I-95 NEAR SAINT PAUL, NC, WHEN HE NOTICED A VAPOR PLUME IN THE REAR VIEW MIRROR. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY EXITED I-95 ONTO STATE ROUTE 20 AND STOPPED AT THE FIRST AVAILABLE SAFE LOCATION. THE DRIVER'S INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE INNER VESSEL PRESSURE HAD RISEN ABOVE 50 PSIG, WHICH OPENED THE MAIN SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. UPON NOTIFYING SUPERVISORY PERSONNEL, THE TRAILER DOWN TO 10 PSIG. AFTER THREE HOURS OF OBSERVATION, THE PRESSURE REMAINED STABLE AT 10 PSIG. THE DRIVER CONTINUED THE TRIP WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENT. UPON COMPLETION OF THE TRIP, A THROUGH INSPECTION OF THE EQUIPMNET WAS PERFORMED. A LEAK CHECK REVEALED THAT THE ANNULAR SPACE VACUUM RELIEF PLATE HAD AN INTERMITTEN VACUUM LEAK, WHICH WOULD EXPLAIN THE SUDDEN RISE IN PRESSURE. THE RELIEF PLATE ASSEMBLY WAS REMOVED, DISAMMBLED, CLEANED, AND REINSTALLED. A 48-HOUR VACUUM RETENTION TEST VERIFIED THAT THE PROBLEM WAS RESOLVED.

THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK CAN ONLY BE SPECULATED NOTING IT LIKELY THAT THE FAILURE OF THE VALVE IS ATTRIBUTED TO NORMAL WEAR AND TEAR. SITE SPECIFIC REVIEWED WITH PERSONNEL TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCE. WE ENCLOSE COPY OF THE BILL OF LADING FOR YOUR PERMANENT RECORD.

THE DERAILMENT WAS THE RESULT OF THE LEFT NO. 1 ROLLER BEARING JOURNAL FAILURE ON CAR SUNX 24805.  AS A RESULT OF THE DERAILMENT, TWO RAIL TANK CARS RELEASED THEIR LADING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE UTLX 641160, LOAD, SPILLED 15,000 GALLONS OF ALCOHOL C12-C14 ETHOXYLATED, ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, N.O.S. AND UTLX 643043, LOAD, SPILLED 20,000 GALLONS OF DIETHANOLAMINE, ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, N.O.S. EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND SUBSEQUENT ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION EFFORTS BY THE KCS, IN CONCERT WITH LOCAL AND STATE OFFICIALS, RESULTED IN THE PROPER CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL OF ALL SPILLED MATERIALS PER LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.

column168: MATERIAL DESCRIBED AS OIL/OILY WATER WAS PUMPED FROM A CUSTOMERS TANK INTO A TWO COMPARTMENT TANKER TRUCK.  THIS MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN THE 2500 GALLON COMPARTMENT WHERE IT BEGAN REACTING WITH THE ALUMINUM OF THE TANKER CAUSING A BUILD UP OF PRESSURE AND TEMPERATURE, RESULTING IN A 200 GALLON RELEASE THROUGH THE VENT.  THE TRUCK WAS STOPPED AND THE SPILL CONTAINED. THE WELDS OF THE TANKER TRUCK RUPTURED RELEASING AN ADDITIONAL 2200 GALLONS OF MATERIAL.  AN EMERGENCY CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED IN TO PERFORM THE CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES.  SAFETY-KLEEN HAS INITIATED A PROGRAM TO LINE THE EXISTING TANKER TRUCKS WITH COATING TO PREVENT SIMILAR EVENTS FROM OCCURRING.  IT WAS DETERMINED FROM ANALYTICAL RESULTS THAT THE MATERIAL HAD A HIGH PH.  THE BRANCH HAS IMPLEMENTED A PH TESTING PROCEDURE FOR ADDED PROTECTION.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ON 6-12-96 AT 3:30 AM, OUR DRIVER, SARINA SHOREY HAD A SPILL AT 4972 BRADLEY BLVD IN BETHESDA,MD  AT THE EXTRA A FUELS GAS STATION.  OUR DRIVER WAS IN OUR COMPANY TRUCK AND TRAILER #21, AND #49.  SHE WAS UNLOADING NL GASOLINE.  THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED WHEN SHE WAS TAKING THE STICK READING. AFTER TAKING THE STICK READING SHE DIDN'T LATCH THE CAP BACK ON WHERE SHE TOOK THE STICK READING FROM ON SECURELY.  WHEN UNLOADING, THE PRESSURE BLEW THE CAP OFF CAUSING A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF NL GASOLINE.  SHE SHUT EVERYTHING OFF AND IMMEDIATELY CALLED HER SUPERVISOR. PHIL WOOLFORD, VICE PRESIDENT WENT TO LOCATION TO ACCESS THE SITUATION. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP ALREADY.  WE NOTIFIED THE MANAGER, MR. MARKOS.  NANCY HARDESTY CALLED E.P.A. AT 9:30 AND AND NOTIFIED AGENCY OF THE SPILL.  SARINA SHOREY WAS WRITTEN AND VERBALLY REPRIMANDED.  SHE WAS WARNED OF THE DANGERS OF NOT FOLLOWING PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES. SHE WILL ALSO RE-TRAINED BY HER SUPERVISOR BEFORE BEING ALLOWED TO RETURN TO WORK.  HARDESTY & SONINC. TAKES HAZARDOUS MATERISALS INCIDENTS VERY SERIOUDLY.  WE ARE DOUBBLE CHECKING EACH EMPLOYEE AND SUB-CONTRACTOR TO VERIFY THEY KNOW AND UNDERSTAND PROPER AND SAFE UNLOADING PROCEDURES.

ON 6-8-96 AT 9:30 AM, OUR DRIVER, DANIEL L DILLINGER, HAD A SPILL AT 4900 BEECH PL., TEMPLE HILLS, MD, AT WASTE MANAGEMENT OF GREATER WASHINGTON. OUR DRIVER WAS IN OUR COMPANY TRUCK AND TRAILER #43 AND #44.  HE WAS UNLOADING HIS TRUCK WITH LSD DIESEL.  HE APPARENTLY DIDN'T HAVE THE FITTING LOCKED ON, THIS CAUSED THE FITTING TO COME UNHOOKED, CAUSING A SPILL.  HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT EVERYTHING OFF AND BEGAN CONTAINING AND CLEANING THE SPILL UP.  HE NOTIFIED WASTE MANAGEMENT'S MANAGER, LEE AYRES. HE CALLED OUR OFFICE AND WE IMMEDIATELY WENT TO LOCATION TO HELP WITH CLEANUP.  NANCY HARDESTY NOTIFIED EPA.  SHE TALKED TO MR HOHENSEE, PCO. DANIEL DILLINGER WAS WRITTEN AND VERBALLY REPRIMANDED.  DUE TO THIS INCIDENT, WE HAVE MADE A NEW COMPANY POLICY OF SECURING HOSE GASKETS AROUND THE COUPLER EARS.  HARDESTY & SONS, INC. TAKES HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INCIDENTS VERY SERIOUSLY.  WE ARE HAVING ADDED SAFETY MEETINGS AND WE ARE RE-TRAINING EMPLOYEES TO ENSURE THIS DOES NO HAPPEN AGAIN.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: ON JUNE 4, 1996, EARLY MORNNG MR. JEFFREY HAM WAS DISPATCHED TO TRANSPORT THE LOAD FROM THE GASTON SC.  TERMINAL TO DELIVER THE LOAD TO PROCHEM CHEMICAL INC.  LOCATED AT 510 W GRIMES ROAD IN HIGH POINT NC.  ENROUTE TO CONSIGNEE (DESTINATION) MR. HAM WAS TRAVELING ON INTERSTATE 77 AT APPROXIMATELY 0815 ON THE OUT SKIRTS OF CHARLOTTE WHEN AN UNKNOWN VEHICLE SUDDENLY CHANGES LANES INFRONT OF HIM AND THEN HIT THE  BRAKES COMING TO A COMPLETE STOP.  MR. HAM DEFENSIVELY APPLIED HIS BRAKES TO AVOID AN ACCIDENT, MAINTAINED CONTROL AND SLOWED THE VEHICLE TO AVOID AN ACCIDENT, MAINTAINED CONTROL AND SLOWED THE VEHICLE TO AVOID STRIKING THE VEHICLE INFROMT OF HIM.  THE WHEELS NEVER LOCKED OR SKIDDED DURING THE APPLICATION OF THE BRAKES.  THE TRAFFIC CONTINUED NORTH BOUND AND MR. HAM PROCEEDED ON TO TO HIS DESTINATION.  AT THIS TIMER MR. HAM WAS NOT AWARE OF THE PROBLEM THAT EXISTED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  WHILE ON INTERSTATE 77 JUST BEFORE THE INTERSECTION OF I-77 AND I-85 A MOTORIST MOTIONED THAT HE HAD A PROBLEM WITH THE UNIT.  BEING LESS THAN (2) MILES FROM THE CHARLOTTE TERMINAL, MR. HAM PROCEEDED TO THE TERMINAL YARD TO INVESTIGATE THE PROBLEM.  ONCE HE ARRIVED AT THE CHARLOTTE YARD, HE REALIZED THAT THE PROBLEM EXISTED WITHIN THE TRAILER.  THE ODOR OF THE CHEMICAL WAS THE INITIAL INDICATION AND ONCE THE VEHICLE CAME TO A STOP HE NOTICED THE PRODUCT LEAKING OUT OF THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS THE MOVED TO A REMOTE AEA SO THAT IT COULD NE DEALT WITH ACCORDING TO THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE BOOK. AT APPROXIMATELY 1030 AM I (MIKE HARLAN) WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  MY LOCATION AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT WAS NORFOLK VA. AND AT THAT TIME CALLED CHARLOTTE TERMINAL AND TALKED TO THE DRIVER MANAGER (STEVE DILLINGER).  WE CONTACTED MR BILL BENNETT WITH SOUTHEASTERN FREIGHT LINBES WHO IS THE SAFETY DIRECTOR FOR THAT TERMINAL MR. BENNETT THEN PROCEEDED TO LOCATE THE NATURE OF THE SPILL AND BEGIN CLEAN UP.  A MSDS WAS OBTAINED FROM ALBRIGHT AND WILSON TO HELP IN THE INVESTIGATION. THE DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACKED DRUM AND THE PRODUCT THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER WAS CONTAINED IN ANOTHER 55 GALLON DRUM. THE PRODUCT WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACKED DRUM AND THE PRODUCT THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER WAS CONTAINED IN ANOTHER 55 GALLON DRUM.  THE PRODUCT ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER WAS ABSORBED WITH QUIK DRY AND LATER PLACED INTO ANOTHER DRUM. THAT NIGHT (6-4-96) THE OTHER 79 DRUMS WERE OFF LOADED AND PLACED ONTO ANOTHER TRAILER FOR DELIVERY THE NEXT DAY.  ONLY ONE DAMAGED PLASTIC DRUM WAS INVOLVED IN THE SPILL.  DURING THE INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS DUE TO LOADING PROCEDURES AND THE LOAD NOT BE SECURED TO PREVENT THE CARGO FROM SHIFTING.  THE SHIPPER HAD PLACED (60 PALLETS IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER, (3) ON EACH SIDE TO MOVED THE CARGO BACK TO ELIMINATE THE TRAILER FROM BEING TOO HEAVY IN THE NOSE.  IN DOING SO THE (3) PALLETS ONLY CAME UP APPROXIMATELY 1/4 OF THE DRUM.  WHEN THE BRAKES WERE APPLIED THE PALLE

column168: MR BRIGMAN GENERLA YARDMASTER, CONTACTED MR. WORS, TRAINMASTER, AT 4:10 AM REGARDING A LEAKING TANK CAR, ETCX 22034, ON THE SOUTH HUMP.  MR. WORS ARRIVED AT THE SOUTH HUMP AT 4:20 AM AND INSPECTED THE TOP COMPARTMENT AND FOUND THAT THE BUTYRALDEHYDE HAD ESCAPED OUT OF ONE OF THE VALVES AND COATED THE LID ON THE INSIDE AND COATED THE VALVES WITH A WHITE THICK SUBSTANCE; SOME CONTENTS SPILLED DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANK CAR AND LEFT A SUBSTANCE THAT WAS BROWN IN COLOR.  THE SUBSTANCE DID HAVE AN ODOR.  MR. WORS SET THE CAR OUT ON THE WEST END OF 124 TRACK IN "C" YARD AT 4:45 AM. AT 5:00 A.M. MR. WORS WAS NOTIFIED THAT MR. L BATEMAN, SWITCHMAN, AND MR. S. MITCHELL, SWITCHMAN, FELT ILL AND WANTED TO BE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL. MR. WORS AND THE TWO EMPLOYEES ARRIVED AT ST. ELIZABETH HOSPITAL IN GRANITE CITY, ILLINOIS AT 5:50AM.

STOTT  DAVIS DRIVER , TIM WEIR WAS MAKING A DELIVERY AT 733 LINDEN AVE., IN ROCHESTER, NY.  HE NOTICED AN ODOR IN TRAILER ANS 1 OF 2 DRUMS DESTINED FOR KAPLAN CONTAINER APPEARED TO BE LEAKING.  TIM WEIR IMMEDIATELY PULLED TRAILER TO LEVEL AREA AND AWAY FROM BUILDING.  UPON OBSERVING DRUMS, ONE WAS LEAKING AND BOTTOM OF OTHER DRUMS WAS IN POOR CONDITION.  IT APPEARED TO HAVE A BULGE ON BOTTOM.  A PALLET JACK THAT HAD BEEN SECURED UNDERNEATH A PALLET MAY HAVE COME LOOSE AND HIT THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM THAT WAS LEAKING.  TIM CALLED DISPATCH VIA TWO-WAY RADIO AND WE SENT A MAN UP WITH SODA ASH AND SPEEDY DRI.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT SHOWED UP APPROXIMATELY 15-25 MINUTES LATER AND OBSERVED THE SITUATION.  MONROE COUNTY RESPONSE TEAM SUPPLIED OVERPACK DRUM AND KAPLAN CONTAINER SUPPLIED OVERPACK DRUM.  BOTH DRUMS WERE PUT IN OVERPACK (RECOVERY) DRUM BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  NYS DEC GAVE US A PERMIT TO HAUL DRUM BACK TO OUR AUBURN FACILITY.  WE NOTIFIED ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS, LIVERPOOL, NY, TO SEND A TEAM TO AUBURN TO HANDLE CLEANING OF ALL HAZARDOUS WASTE AND CLEANING OF TRAILER.  ALL DRUMS AREA NOW TO BE BLOCKED WITH DUNNAGE ON ALL SIDES.  ANY DRUMS THAT APPEARS TO BE IN POOR CONDITION MUST BE HELD AND NOT OUT FOR DELIVERY UNTIL PROPER INSPECTION CAN BE MADE.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: MR RODRIGUEZ AND MS LUNA CHECKED IN FOR FLIGHT 973 TO LIMA AT 2041.  THEY CHECKED THREE BAGS.  AT APPROXIMATELY 2050, ONE OF THE BAGS WAS DISCOVERED SMOLDERING AND BURNING IN THE BAGGAGE MAKE-UP AREA.  A CSR WORKING THE BAG ROOM EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE WITH WATER.  CUSTOMER SERVICE SUPERVISOR, LARRY GRIFFIN WAS NOTIFIED. MR GRIFFIN HAD THE BAG ALONG WITH THE OTHER TWO BAGS BROUGHT TO THE BACK OFFICE OF BAGGAGE SERVICE.  UPON OPENING THE BAG, IT WAS DISCOVERED THE BAG CONTAINED A CAMERAMAN'S POWER PACK BELT WITH NI-CAD BATTERIES, A BATTERY CHARGER, CABLES AND A HIGH INTENSITY LAMP.  IT BECAME APPARENT THAT DURING HANDLING A SMALL RED BUTTON, LOCATED ON THE BELT, WAS PUSHED ON; CAUSING THE LAMP TO POWER UP.  THE HEAT CREATED BY THE LAMP SET THE BAG BURNING.  THE CABLES FROM THE POWER PACK TO THE LAMP WERE STILL CONNECTED.  MR GRIFFIN PAGED THE CUSTOMERS TO THE BAGGAGE SERVICE OFFICE AND INTERVIEWED THE CUSTOMERS.  MR RODRIGUEZ STATED THAT HE HAD PACKED THE SOFT SIDED BAG.  HE WENT ON TO SAY HE HAD TRAVELED MANY TIMES WITH THIS EQUIPMENT AND HAD NEVER DISCONNECTED THE CABLES FROM THE POWER PACK.  THE OTHER TWO BAGS WERE HAND SEARCHED AND CLEARED.  THE CUSTOMERS WERE ALLOWED TO CONTINUE THEIR TRIP.  MR GRIFFIN TOOK PHOTOGRAPHS OF THE BURNT BAG AND ITS CONTENTS. MR GRIFFIN CALLED THE DANGEROUS GOODS HOT LINE AND SPOKE TO REPRESENTATIVE GORDON.  MR GORDON CONFIRMED THAT NO SPECIAL PACKING OR HANDLING WAS REQUIRED TO THIS TYPE OF BATTERY. ON THE ADVICE OF WHQFS, CARL KOLE, THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE FAA SOUTH REGION OFFICE ONMONDAY, JUNE 10, 1996 AT 10:15 AM TO AGENT CHUCK SHAFFER (404) 305-6851. ALLAGENTS ARE BEING BRIEFED ON THIS INCIDENT.

column168: DOCKMAN DISCOVERED THE LEAKING PAIL WHILE UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM THE INBOUND TRAILER.  THE BOTOM OF THE PAIL HAD SUFFERED METAL FATIGUE DUE TO THE CONSTANT VIBRATION OF THE METAL BOTTOM AGAINST THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE ORGIN TERMINAL FREIGHT LOADER FAILED TO USE CARDBOARD DUNNAGE BETWEEN THE BOTTOM OF THE PAIL AND THE TRAILER FLOOR.  PAIL TRANSFERRED TO OS & D FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  DOCK PERSONNEL SHOULD ALWAYS PLACED CARDBOARD DUNNAGE BETWEEN METAL PAILS AND METAL DRUMS AND THE TRAILER FLOOR TO REDUCE THE POSSIBILITY OF METAL FATIGUE.

column168: I ARRIVED AT RISE APPROXIMATELY 10:15 A.M. WITH A SHIPMENT OF FIVE SKIDS FROM VICTORY GRAPHICS, OAK CREEK, WI.  IN FRONT OF THE SHIPMENT OF RISE WAS A SHIPMENT FOR INX INTERNATIONAL, APPLETON, WI.  ALSO BEHIND TOWARD THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WAS A SKID I ALREADY PICKED UP AT PEARSON CANDY. ****** I ALERTED THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR I HAD A SHIPMENT FOR THEM BUT SHE WOULD FIRST HAVE TO MOVE THE FREIGHT THAT BLOCKED HERS.  I WENT IN TO THE TRAILER AND POINTED OUT WHICH SKIDS WERE HERS AND WHICH SKIDS NEEDED TO BE UNLOADED TO GET AT HERS.  I STOOD ON THE DOCK PLATE ON THE DRIVER SIDE OF THE TRAILER.  SHE FIRST UNLOADED ONE SKID OF PRODUCT BELONGING TO INX. THEN SHE UNLOADED A SKID OF HER PRODUCT.  SHE THEN DROVE BACK IN TO THE TRAILER TO GET THE LAST SKID OF INX PRODUCT OFF.  SHE HAD HER FORKS TOO HIGH AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM APPROXIMATELY 2.5" - 3" FROM THE BOTTOM. ****** THERE WAS NOTHING BLOCKING HER VIEW OR PATH TO OR AROUND THE SKID OF DRUMS.  I COULD NOT DIRECTLY SEE HER PUNCTURE THE DRUM BECAUSE I WAS STANDING DIRECTLY BEHIND HER FORKLIFT ON THE DOCK PLATE.  SHE THEN EXCLAIMED TO ME SHE PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  I TOLD HER IMMEDIATELY TO GET OUT OF THE TRAILER AND GET SAND, GRAVEL, FLOOR DRY, AND ANYTHING ELSE WE COULD USE TO STOP LEAKAGE ON TO THE DOCK OR GROUND. ******  WE ENDED UP USING EVERYTHING FROM CARDBOARD, SAND, FLOOR DRY, AND PLASTIC BAGS WITH SAND IN THEM.  THE PRODUCT NEVER GOT ON TO THE DOCK, BUT IT DID SEEP THROUGH THE CRACKS IN THE FLOOR ON TO THE UNDERCARRIAGE OF THE TRAILER AND DRIPPED DOWN ON THE GROUND.  ***** AFTER WE HAD CONTAINED THE SPILL AS BEST WE COULD, I BEGAN TO MAKE PHONE CALLS TO STEVE SPLETTER (TERMINAL MGR.) AND CARY KRICKEBERG (SAFETY MANAGER) TO INFORM THEM OF THE SPILL AND WHAT HAD BEEN DONE TO THAT POINT TO STOP THE SPREAD OF PRODUCT. ******  (END OF STATEMENT BY DRIVER ROD JOHNSON) **** RISE INC, DID CALL BAY WEST INC, ST. PAUL, MN FOR THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CLEAN UP.  OTHER AGENCIES CONTACTED WERE THE LOCAL POLICE AND HEALTH DEPARTMENT.  FINAL CLEAN UP DETAILS, AS WELL AS DISPOSAL OF ALL HAZARDOUS WASTE MATERIALS WAS HANDLED BY BAY WEST. DECONTAMINATION OF THE TRAILER WAS BY A LOCAL TANK WASH FACILITY IN NEENAH, WI AT THE DIRECTION OF THE N & M TRANSFER SAFETY DEPARTMENT.

column168: ON JUNE 26, 1996, AT APPROXIMATELY 6:15 AM, DONALD A. LEDGERWOOD AN EMPLOYEE OF BROWN TRANSFER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING FREIGHT AND RELOADING FREIGHT ON ANOTHER TRAILER, HE NOTICED FLUID ON THE FLOOR WHICH HE THOUGHT WAS COMING FROM A LEAKING BOX ON A PALLET.  WHEN HE FOUND THAT THE PALLET WAS NOT DAMAGED, HE LOOKED AT THE BULK TANK OR TOTE TANK THAT WAS SETTING NEXT TO IT.  THIS PARTICULAR CONTAINER HELD APPROXIMATELY 300 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID (93.2%, FUMING SULFURIC ACID).  HE REACHED DOWN AND LOOKED UNDER THE TANK AND COULD NOT SEE ANYTHING DRIPPING, AT WHICH TIME HE PUT HIS HAND ON THE CONTROL VALVE WHICH BURST FROM THE ACID CONTAINER, SPRAYING THE EMPLOYEE'S ARM, FACE, LEG, AND ANKLES WITH THE PRODUCT.  HE IMMEDIATELY ATTEMPTED TO WASH THE SULFURIC ACID OFF OF HIS BODY IN THE BATHROOM AT THE TERMINAL FACILITY AND THEN WENT BACK OUT, PUTTING ON RUBBER GLOVES, AND REINSERTING THE ENTIRE VALVE UNIT BACK INTO THE BULK TANK TO PREVENT IT FROM LEAKING ANY FURTHER.  HE WAS TRANSPORTED BY PRIVATE VEHICLE TO SAINT FRANCIS MEDICAL CENTER GRAND ISLAND, NE., WHERE HE WAS TREATED FOR CHEMICAL BURNS.  HE WAS RELEASED HOME THAT SAME MORNING.

UPON ARRIVAL AIRCRAFT HAS SECURED AND PPE WAS DONNED TO CONTINUE THE INVESTIGATION. AFTER FINDING THE ODOROUS SHIPMENT WE BEGAN OUR INSPECTION. THIS WAS A PLAIN BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX WITH NO MARKINGS OR LABELS TO INDICATE THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL. THE ONLY ATTACHED PAPERWORK WAS AN INTERNATIONAL BILL OF LADING. IT WAS ESTIMATED APPROX 6 OZS. LEAKED AROUND THE FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE AND THE PRODUCT DID PENETRATE THE FIBERBOARD BOX. THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD PENDING A FAA INVESTIGATION. THERE WERE NO INDICATIONS OF ANY KIND THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL. THIS WILL BE HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTIL RELEASED BY THE FAA.

column168: REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L. WHITELEY, PORTLAND, OR., WAS NOTIFIED BY HINKLE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT FORCES THAT TANK CAR PLMX 2802 WAS NOTED ON ARRIVAL RECEIVING TRACK #6, LEAKING FROM TOP OF TANK CAR. WHITELEY ARRANGED FOR ISOLATION OF TANK CAR AND TRAVELED TO LOCATION ON JUNE 5, 1996. INSPECTION FOUND SOURCE OF LEAK FROM UNDER HINGED MANWAY COVER LID. LID WAS PROTECTED BY INTACT SEAL PHILLIPS 66 CO 04181. REMOVED SEAL OPENED MANWAY AND FOUND THAT NO MANWAY GASKET HAD BEEN INSTALLED WHEN CAR WAS LOADED AND SHIPPED. A GASKET WAS INSTALLED, EIGHT SWING BOLT MANWAY LID SECURED. SEAL UPY 753782 APPLIED FOR PROTECTION. CHEMTREC JOE DEBMAN FURNISHED DETAILS. PHILLIPS 66 TONY BLACK, WOODS CROSS, UT., FURNISHED DETAILS VIA VOICE MAIL.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: ON 060396 AT 1000 HRS TRANSPORTATION DIRECTOR D. BURNS CONTACTED CTS MGR. M. KELLY AND ADVISED THAT HE HAD BEEN CONTACTED BY THE TULSA, OK. FIRE DEPT. WITH REFERENCE TO POSSIBILITY TWO LEAKING TANK CARS. KELLY CONTACTED CAPT. R. BRASFIELD WITH THE TULSA FIRE DEPT. WHO STATED THAT HIS DEPT HAD RECEIVED A CALL FROM A BUSINESS LOCATED NEAR THE TRACKS WHERE THE TWO TANK CAR WERE LOCATED COMPLAINING OF A STRONG CHEMICAL ODOR. BRASFIELD TOLD KELLY THAT WHEN THEIR HAZ/MAT TEAM ARRIVED ON THE SCENE THEY INSPECTED THE TWO TANK CARS WITH FLAMMABILITY RANGE METERS AND DISCOVERED THAT THE VAPORS WERE COMING OUT FROM UNDER THE MANWAY COVER. BRASFIELD ADVISED THAT THE TEAM TIGHTENED ALL THE SWING BOLTS ON THE MANWAY COVER AND AGAIN RAN A TEST ON THE AREA, THIS TIME WITH NEGATIVE RESULTS. THE TWO CARS WERE THEN TRANSPORTED TO DESTINATION AT SINCLAIR REFINING IN TULSA. AFTER OFFLOADING THEIR PRODUCT KELLY INSPECTED THE MANWAY GASKETS IN BOTH CARS AND FOUND THAT THEY WERE VERY WORN, WITH CRACKS COMPLETLY THROUGH THE GASKET MATERIAL IN SEVERAL LOCATIONS. KELLY REPLACED THE MANWAY GASKETS IN BOTH CARS. THE OTHER CAR INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT WAS UTLX 201921.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW, DURING COMPLIANCE INSPECTION OF TRAIN CYDE-4, EXTRA 3798 SOUTH, NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM LOW PROFILE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. INSPECTION REVEALED VALVE WAS CRACKED OPEN. FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT BOTTOM OUTLET CAP GASKET WAS DAMAGED. CLOSED VALVE AND REPLACED DAMAGED GASKET, WHICH STOPPED LEAK. CHRIS YOUNG, CHEMTREC, FILE #44732 AND BERRY CUNNINGHAM, COASTAL REFINING MARKETING, HOUSTON, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS. BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS WITHOUT SEAL. AFTER REPAIR APPLIED SEAL; UP-U-209332.

APPROXIMATELY 0830 HRS ON 060596, SPECIALIST CTS RICHARD TUFTS RECEIVED A CALL FROM MANAGER CAR MAINT. PROVISO, BOB PORTNER, THAT CAR #PLMX2558, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS, LIQUIFIED, WAS LEAKING VAPOR FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. SPECIALIST TUFTS CONTACTED REGIONAL MANAGER CTS TOM ROBINSON TO ADVISE AND THEN TRAVELED FROM ST. LOUIS TO CHICAGO IN RESPONSE. AT APPROX. 0921 HRS, CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED, BROOK WEBBER, AND CONTACT WITH SHIPPER, KOCH NITROGEN CO., SONYA NEWRY, 316-828-5667 AND CONSIGNEE TERRA NITROGEN CORP., TIM EAST, 918-660-6267, WAS MADE TO ADVISE SITUATION. UPON ARRIVAL AT PROVISO YARD, MGR. PORTNER ACCOMPANIED SPECIALIST TUFTS TO LOCATION WHERE CAR HAD BEEN ISOLATED. INSPECTION WAS MADE WITH THE FOLLOWING PROBLEMS/DEFECTS NOTED. VAPOR ESCAPING FROM PACKING GLAND NUT ON GAUGING DEVICE, ALL VALVES (2 LIQUID & 1 VAPOR) LOOSE 1/4-1/2 TURN, LIQUID LINE POSITIONED TO "A" END OF CAR PLUG LESS THAN HAND TIGHT, VAPOR LINE PLUG LESS THAN HAND TIGHT, LIQUID LINE TO "B" END OF CAR 2-3 TURNS LOOSE, BUT AT LEAST HAND TIGHT, SAFETY RELIEF VALVE HAD TWO SECUREMENT BOLTS LOOSE AT POINT OF ATTACHMENT TO MANWAY COVER PLATE, AND SAMPLE LINE NEEDLE VALVE LOOSE 1/2-3/4 TURN. ALL LOOSE NUTS, VALVES, AND PLUGS WERE PROPERLY TIGHTENED IN EFFORT TO STOP VENTING OF VAPOR. WHEN THIS FAILED, SPECIALIST TUFTS LOOSENED THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE GAUGING DEVICE AND NOTING THAT THERE WAS NO PACKING MATERIAL PRESENT, PACKED THE NUT WITH GORTEX AND RESECURED THE NUT. ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE TESTED WITH SULPHUR STICKS, AMMONIA TEST PAPER AND FINALLY WITH SNOOP AND CAR WAS FOUND TO BE SECURE. SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE NOTIFIED OF FINDINGS AND REMEDIAL ACTIONS TAKEN.

WHILE TANK CAR WAS LOCATED AT THE UNION PACIFIC YARD AT LIVONIA, LOUISIANA, YARD PERSONNEL DETECTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. THE CAR WAS LOCATED IN TRACK 500 AND NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO T. M. ROBINSON, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY. ROBINSON RESPONDED ALONG WITH MR. P.J. STUDENT, MANAGER TECHNICAL RESOUCES. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM A FAILED GASKET BETWEEN THE LIQUID VALVE FLANGE AND THE EDUCTION PIPE FLANGE. THE LEAKING PRODUCT WAS RUNNING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR AND EVAPORATING BEFORE IT COULD HIT THE GROUND. PRESSURE WAS RELIEVED BY OPENING THE AIR VALVE AND THIS STOPPED THE LEAKAGE. THE FOUR STUD BOLTS WERE REMOVED FROM THE FLANGE ASSEMBLY AND FURTHER INSPECTION INDICATED THE OLD GASKET OF GORTEK WAS APPLIED AND THE FLANGE ASSEMBLY WAS REASSEMBLED. THIS SECURED THE CAR FOR INSPECTION. ALTHOUGH NO SEALS WERE PREVIOUSLY PRESENT, THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND MANWAY COVER WERE SECURED WITH SEALS UP-A354952 AND A354953. CHEMTREC COMMUNICATOR CHRIS YOUNG WAS NOTIFIED. ROBINSON GOT A CALL BACK FROM MR. BILLY MCCULLOGH FROM EXXON CHEMICALS AMERICAS. MCCULLOGH WAS ADVISED OF THE LEAKAGE AND CORRECTIVE MEASURES TAKEN.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: ON 06/05/96 AT APPROXIMATELY 3PM, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER, RECEIVED A CALL FROM PAM AT UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT THAT THE ABOVE CONTAINER WAS LEAKING. SHE HAS ISOLATED THE TRAILER IN A REMOTE LOCATION. THE LEAK WAS SMALL AND APPEARED TO BE A THICK, CLEAR LIQUID. REEDER CONTACTED SHAWNA AT MEDITERRANEAN SHIPPING, THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE. SHE CALLED EMTECH ENVIRONMENTAL SEVICE TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT. CHIP DAY WAS ON SCENE FOR EMTECH. HE OPENED THE TRAILER AND FOUND IT LOADED WITH STEEL BEAMS AND FOUR DRUMS OF PAINT. THERE WAS NO BLOCKING AND BRACING IN THE TRAILER. THE BEAMS HAD SHIFTED AND PUNCTURED ONE OF THE DRUMS. THE PUNCTURED DRUM WAS EMPTY. THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER CONTAINER. THIS CONTAINER WAS RELEASED TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR THEIR HANDLING.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings; Vent
column168: MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW, DURING COMPLIANCE INSPECTION OF TRAIN CYOG-6 EXTRA CNW8715 WEST, NORTH 5 TRACK, CHEYENNE, NOTED PRODUCT COMING FROM TOP OF TANK CAR. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT BS&B 100# FRANGIBLE DISK WITH NEW BS&B 100# DISC, WHICH STOPPED LEAK. GATX SAFETY VENT WAS MOUNTED UPON THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. BROOKS WEBBER, CHEMTREC, FILE #44822 AND JEFF VONLINPEL, VAN WATERS ROGERS, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.

AT 2030 HRS ON FRIDAY THE 7TH DAY OF JUNE, MGR RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY MR ALAN HILL, MTO AT SALT LAKE REGARDING A LEAKING TANK CAR KCCX2248.  IT WAS REPORTED BY YARD PERSONNEL THAT PRODUCT WAS RUNNING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR.  INSPECTION UPON ARRIVAL REVEALED THE FRANGIBLE DISC TO BE BROKEN, WITH PRODUCT AT THE TOP OF THE SAFETY VENT, INDICATING THE CAR TO BE OVERFILLED.  MGR RODABOUGH APPLIED A NEW DISC AND NOTIFIED KENNECOTT UTAH COPPER, MR GREGG GEARHARDT WHO MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE CAR MOVED BACK TO THE PLANT WHERE A PORTION OF THE LOAD WAS REMOVED.  THIS WAS ACCOMPLISHED ON JUNE THE 9TH, IT WAS CONFIRMED THAT THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED. PLANS HAVE BEEN FORMED TO PREVENT THIS FROM OCCURRING IN THE FUTURE.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION, D.A. LOW, WAS CONTACTED BY CHEYENNE YARD MASTER, THAT EAST END SWITCH CREW WHILE SWITCHING CUT FROM WEST TO EAST HAD MISTAKENLY LINED THE NORTH CROSS OVER SWITCH FROM NORTH THREE INTO NORTH FIVE TRACK.  TANK CAR GATX 70026 WAS ON POINT AND STRUCK CYOG-15 TRAIN LOCATED ON NORTH FIVE TRACK, DERAILING TANK CAR AND EMPTY COVER HOPPERS ON CYOG-15. ***** INSPECTION REVEALED THAT LEFT SIDE OF TANK CAR OVER L-4 AND ABOUT HALF WAY DOWN SIDE OF CAR HAD A 3 FOOT BY 4 INCH HOLE THROUGH SHELL.  ALSO, ON 'A' END TANK HEAD, LOWER LEFT CORNER HAD A 2 INCH CRACK.  JACKET MATERIAL LEFT SIDE AND TANK HEAD, 'A' END WAS RIPPED AWAY FROM DAMAGED SHELL.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT A WHEEL HAD PENETRATED JACKET AND SHELL.  PLUGGED HOLES, WHICH REDUCED THE LEAK. TRANSFERRED 9,513 GALLONS INTO TRUCKS, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  ****** TRACY JACKSON, CHEMTREC, FILE #45108, GENE GOETZ, WILLIAM WEAVER, SINCLAIR OIL AND THE WYOMING STATE DEQ, WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

AT 0015 HRS 06/17/96, UNION PACIFIC EMPLOYEES REPORTED PRODUCT COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 23074 WHILE CAR WAS BEING SWITCHED IN THE COUNCIL BLUFFS, IA, RAILYARD.  LEAK SUBSIDED WHEN CAR WAS AT REST.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SUBSEQUENTLY INSPECTED BY UNION PACIFIC SPECIAL AGENT KEN DECHANT AT 0130 HRS SAME DATE.   DECHANT NOTED THE QUICK-OPENING FILL HOLE GASKET WAS IMPROPERLY POSITIONED, WITH THE GASKET SURFACE OUTSIDE THE FILL HOLE COVER FOR APPROXIMATELY 40% OF ITS CIRCUMFERENCE, AND NOT SEALING IN THAT AREA.  ALL SPILLAGE APPEARED BENEATH THAT LOCATION, AND ALL OTHER FITTINGS WERE FOUND TO BE SECURE.  DECHANT REPOSITIONED THE GASKET AND SECURED THE COVER.  CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT 0235 HRS.  FILL HOLE COVER WAS PROTECTED BY SEAL UP-2424149, WHICH WAS REMOVED TO ALLOW REPOSITIONING OF THE GASKET, THEN RESEALED WITH UPE-277480 FOLLOWING REPAIR.  CHEMTREC FILE #45153.

ON 061996 AT APPROXIMATELY 630 PM, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER, RECEIVED A CALL FROM MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, TERESA LAWLER, THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED BY A CARMAN DURING ROUTINE INSPECTION OF AN OUTBOUND TRAIN. UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER NOTICED A DRIBBLE TYPE STAIN ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR THAT APPEARED TO HAVE COME FROM THE MANWAY.  THE CAR WAS DRY.  REEDER REMOVED SEAL PAKTANK 297527 FROM THE MANWAY COVER SAFETY BOLT AND OPENED THE COVER.  THE MANWAY GASKET WAS CRIMPED AND CUT NEAR THE HINGE.  REEDER FORMED A NEW GASKET FROM GORE-TEX AND SECURED THE MANWAY COVER.  THE CAR WAS RESEALED WITH UNION PACIFIC 844324.  THE SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED.

DURING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, SPECIALIST CTS RICHARD TUFTS NOTED PRODUCT SEEPING FROM MALE PLUG CAP ON LIQUID VALVE ASSEMBLY.  LEAK RESULTED FROM VALVE BEING APPROXIMATELY 1/8 TURN OPEN.  SPECIALIST TUFTS CLOSED VALVE WHICH CORRECTED PROBLEM AND STOPPED THE LEAK.  SHIPPER NOTIFIED.

DURING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, SPECIALIST CTS RICHARD TUFTS NOTED VAPOR ESCAPING FROM A LOOSE OFF LOAD FITTING THAT HAD BEEN IMPROPERLY SECURED.  CONTACTED CONSIGNEE, MONTGOMERY TANK LINES, WHOSE EMPLOYEE RESPONDED AND PROPERLY SECURED THE FITTING.

column168: REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L. WHITELEY, PORTLAND, OR., WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS UNION PACIFIC HINKLE YARD, HINKLE, OR., OBSERVED PRODUCT STAINING SIDES AND DRIPPING OFF BOTTOM OUTLET SKID PROTECTION TANK CAR UTLX 59554, NA-1993, SPOTTED RECEIVING TRACK #3.  RELEASE WAS FROM AREA UNDER COMBINATION HOUSING COVER WHICH WAS PROTECTED BY INTACT SEAL AMOCO 3111.  INSPECTION DEVELOPED BLIND FLANGE LIQUID EDUCTION BALL VALVE ASSEMBLY WAS TILTED AT POINT WHERE 4 STUD BOLTS SECURE ASSEMBLY TO TANK CAR ALLOWING PRODUCT TO BY-PASS GASKET/FLANGE.  ATTEMPTS TO RE-POSITION ASSEMBLY WERE NEGATIVE. LOOSENED 4 STUD BOLTS, LIFTED ASSEMBLY AND INSERTED GORTEX GASKET MATERIAL UNDERNEATH FLANGE AND RESECURED.  TANK CAR DISPLAYED 4 COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID CLASS 3 PLACARDS.  EXAMINATION OF SHIPPING PAPERS NOTED CAR BILLED ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S. (DECANTED OIL), CLASS 9, UN3257. CONTACTED DOUG FOSTER, CRYSEN REFINERY, WHO ADVISED TANK CAR WAS LOADED BY AMOCO REFINERY, SALT LAKE CITY, UT.  KATHY KOOPMANN, AMOCO, WAS ALSO CONTACTED AND SHIPPING DESCRIPTION WAS CORRECTED TO READ FUEL OIL (RESIDUAL, DECANTED, OIL).  SEAL UPY 753717 APPLIED FOR PROTECTION. HINGED MANWAY LID PROTECTED BY INTACT SEAL AMOCO 3110, BOTTOM OUTLET OPERATING HANDLE PROTECTED BY INTACK SEAL AMOCO 3121.  TANK CAR WILL BE SHOPPED FOR REPAIRS WHEN UNLOADED.

column168: MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D. A. LOW, WAS NOTIFIED BY WEST END SWITCH CREW, THAT A STRONG GAS LIKE ODOR WAS COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX 16991, SOUTH 3 TRACK, CHEYENNE YARDS.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT ALL 6 MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE SECURED PROPERLY.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT MANWAY GASKET HAD FAILED.  APPLIED GORE-TEX GASKET, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  NANCY MOEBIUS, MERICHEM, WAS NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, VERN LIBBY WAS NOTIFIED THAT CONTAINER EMPU 180330 WAS AT THE UPMF RAMP, PORTLAND, OREGON AND NOTED TO HAVE A STRONG CHEMICAL ODOR.  THE CONTAINER WAS NOT VISIBLY LEAKING.  HE WAS ADVISED THAT THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN ISOLATED FOR THE NIGHT AND WOULD BE RE-EVALUATED IN THE MORNING.  LIBBY WAS ADVISED BY J. D. HAHN, SPECIAL AGENT, PORTLAND, AT APPROXIMATELY 1855 HRS., 06/24, THAT HE HAD INSPECTED THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION AND IT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING ON THE RIGHT SIDE NEAR THE MIDDLE OF THE CONTAINER.  HAHN ADVISED HE WOULD PLACE A BUCKET UNDER THE LEAK. ****** LIBBY ARRIVED AT THE SITE AT 1000 HRS., 06/25 AT WHICH TIME HE NOTED THE LEAK HAHN HAD DESCRIBED TO BE RESIDUE RAIN WATER.  HOWEVER FURTHER INSPECTION DEVELOPED A CHEMICAL LEAK IN THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER. IT APPEARED TO BE HANGING AND COAGULATED.  AN INTERIOR INSPECTION OF CONTAINER EMPU 180330 WAS CONDUCTED DEVELOPING THE FOLLOWING.  - NO BLOCKING OR BRACING.  - 12 METAL 55 GALLON DRUMS OF MASCO 14% CURE SEAL FD UV LOADED IN THE NOSE OF CONTAINER.  - THE FLOOR APPEARED TO BE SHINNY AND WET.  HOWEVER THE PORTION PRODUCT THAT HAD LEAKED WAS DRYING AND COAGULATING.  LIBBY CONTACTED ROY ALLEN, HUB CITY, PORTLAND, LOCAL CONSIGNEE'S REPRESENTATIVE AND ADVISED HIM THAT THE CONTAINER WAS NOT LEAKING AND THE PORTION OF PRODUCT THAT HAD PREVIOUSLY LEAKED WAS DRY AND COAGULATED.  THEREFORE IF HIS CLIENT WOULD ACCEPT THE CONTAINER FOR DELIVERY IT COULD BE DELIVERED AS IS. ****** A JOINT AGREEMENT BETWEEN ALL PARTIES INVOLVED WAS ACHIEVED AND CONTAINER IN QUESTION WAS SCHEDULED FOR DELIVERY IN THE AM OF 06/16.  LIBBY REQUESTED THAT HE BE ADVISED HOW MANY OF THE DRUMS LEAKED, WHAT CAUSED THE LEAK, AND THE DRUM SPECIFICATIONS FROM THE CONSIGNEE.  HOWEVER TO DATE, THE DRUM SPECIFICATIONS HAVE NOT BEEN RECEIVED.  LIBBY WAS ADVISED THAT 1 OF 12 DRUMS LEAKED DUE TO A PUNCTURE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, VERN LIBBY WAS NOTIFIED THAT KEN KUBIC, MYO, FIFE/SEATTLE REPORTED TANK CAR UTLX 200566 LEAKING AT THE TOP IN THE MANWAY AREA DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED PENDING AN INSPECTION.  INVESTIGATION DEVELOPED THE FOLLOWING:  - LMB49 25, CONDUCTOR DENNIS SCOTT, REPORTED THIS INCIDENT TO HIS SUPERVISOR KEN KUBIC.  - SCOTT ALSO CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE MATLACK INC., KENT, WA.  - LIBBY CONTACTED VINCE HELT, MATLACK INC. AND IN HIS ABSENCE, MR. HELT AND GARY CLARKE, MAINTENANCE SUPERVISOR MATLACK INC., HANDLED THIS INCIDENT. HELT ADVISED THE FOLLOWING WHEN THE TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED:  - HE FOUND NO PRODUCT ON THE EXTERIOR OF TANKCAR IN QUESTION.  - HE FOUND NO PRODUCT ON THE GROUND UNDER THE TANKCAR.  - HE NOTED THE CAP OF THE MIDLAND FILTER VENT DAMP.  - FURTHER INSPECTION DEVELOPED APPROXIMATELY 5 OZ. OF PRODUCT ON TOP OF THE FILTER.  - HE USED A SUCTION TUBE AND REMOVED THE EXCESS PRODUCT.  - HE CLOSED AND SECURED THE MIDLAND FILTER VENT CAP.  - HE NOTED NO OTHER EXCEPTIONS.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT ZERWECK WHILE DOING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, FOUND CAR GATX 7365 WITH THE FRANGIBLE DISC RUPTURED.  THE 100 LB STAINLESS DISC WAS REPLACED WITH A BS&B 100 LB STAINLESS DISC AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.  ZERWECK CONTACTED RON JACOBS AT PHELPS DODGE AND MADE HIM AWARE OF THE DISC REPLACEMENT.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, VERN LIBBY WAS CONTACTED BY CUSTOMER SVCS. SUPERVISOR, ALASKA RAILROAD, SEATTLE, AT APPROXIMATELY 1515 HRS., 06/27. HE ADVISED, TANKCAR TIEX 3069, LOCATED AT HARBOR ISLAND, SEATTLE APPEARED TO BE WET ON THE SIDE OF THE TANKCAR.  HOWEVER, THE GROUND UNDER THE TANKCAR WAS DRY.  LIBBY MADE CONTACT WITH KEVIN MEIER, CUSTOMER SVCS SUPERVISOR AND TOGETHER THEY INSPECTED TANKCAR TIEX 3069.  - THE TANKCAR IN QUESTION WAS LOCATED IN TRACK 19 HARBOR ISLAND.  - THE GROUND UNDER THE TANKCAR WAS NOTED DRY.  - THERE APPEARED TO BE A RESIDUE OF THE PRODUCT ON THE SIDE OF THE TANKCAR.  HOWEVER, IT WAS DRY AND STICKY.  3 OF 6 MANWAY COVER SWING BOLTS FINGER LOOSE.  - STANDING AT THE HINGE FACING THE MANWAY COVER THE 3 LOOSE SWING BOLTS WERE LOCATED AT THE 11, 1 AND 3 O'CLOCK POSITION.  - AT THE 12 O'CLOCK POSITION THE LIFT HANDLE HAD BEEN WELDED TO THE MANWAY COVER WITH THE 11 AND 1 O'CLOCK SWING BOLTS LOCATED TO THE LEFT AND RIGHT OF IT.  - THE SWING BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED SECURING THE MANWAY COVER LID.  MEIER, ALASKA RAILROAD, AGREED TO EXCEPT TANKCAR TIEX 3069, ON BEHALF OF THE ALASKA RAILROAD FOR DELIVERY TO CONSIGNEE.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: AT TIME OF DELIVERY THE PUNCTURE WAS FOUND IN DRUM AND CLEANUP WAS DONE BY HYDRITE CHEMICAL IN COTTAGE GROVE, WI.  INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO BLANCHARD; REPORT NO. 349594.  800-424-8802.

column42: BLACK POWDER OR GUNPOWDER, GRANULAR OR AS A MEAL
column168: FROM CHRIS E. LAWRENCE, SUBJECT:  MEM FLIGHT 28 TO DCA.  A/320 6/14/96 TONIGHT, I WAS CALLED OUT TO FLIGHT 28 AIRCRAFT 3248 BECAUSE THE BACK BIN HAD A ODOR OF SMOKE OR SOMETHING BURNING... UPON INVESTIGATING BY A/C MAINTENANCE AND OUR ESE/ESC WORK FORCE WE FOUND THAT THE SMOKE ODOR WAS COMING FROM A LARGE PIECE OF LUGGAGE... I TOOK THE BAG TO THE CENTER CHECKPOINT WHERE I X-RAYED THE BAG..WE FOUND A SPOT THAT NEEDED CHECKING AND I OPENED THE BAG AND FOUND A 10CAP BLASTING MACHINE CAPACITY SERIAL NO.S10-90BJ.  ALSO WHEN WE OPENED THE BAG THE SMELL WAS OVERWHELMING OF GUN POWDER...ALSO I NOTICED THE PERSONNEL BAG TAG OF AN FBI CARD.  I WENT BACK TO THE AIRCRAFT WHERE WE PT THE JETBRIDGE BACK ON AND I INFORMED THE CAPTAIN OF WHAT WE HAD FOUND AND WHAT I WAS GOING TO DO ABOUT IT.  I PAGED FBI AGENT TIMOTHY PETROUSKY (PHYSICAL SCIENCE TECHNICIAN) OFF THE A/C AND I INTRODUCTED MYSELF WITH MY CARD.  I EXPLAINED THAT WE THOUGHT WE HAD A FIRE IN THE LUGGAGE BIN BECAUSE OF THE HIGH ODOR FROM THIS LUGGAGE. I ASKED TO SEE HIS ID WHICH HE SHOWED ME AND TO EXPLAIN TO ME WHAT THIS WAS DOING IN HIS LUGGAGE.  HE INFORMED ME THAT THEY WERE IN MEMPHIS AND WAS AT THE BLASTING RANGE WITH THIS BLASTING MACHINE... HE SAID THAT IT WAS PERFECTLY O.K. AND THAT THIS DID NOT HAVE ANY EXPLOSIVES BUT WAS JUST A GENERATOR.  I ASKED IF HE HAD ANYTHING ELSE IN HIS BAG LIKE THIS OR ANY OTHER ITEMS OF A NATURE THAT COULD BE CLASSIFIED AS DANGEROUS.  I WAS TOLD "NO" AND SINCE HE WAS TRAVELING WITH A GROUP... DID ANY OF THE OTHERS HAVE ANY ITEMS OF THIS IN THEIR LUGGAGE... I WAS TOLD "NO" AGAIN.  AT THIS TIME, OTHER AGENTS OF THE FBI HAD COME OFF TO THE JETBRIDGE AND GAVE ASSURANCES THAT THIS WAS THE ONLY ITEM OF THIS KIND... I REFUSED TO LET THIS ITEM GO ON THE AIRCRAFT AND THAT I WOULD CALL THE LOCAL FBI OFFICE IN MEMPHIS AND THEY COULD PICK-UP AND RETURN TO HIM BY FED EX OR SOME OTHER WAY THAN BY NWA.  I EXPLAINED THE REASON BECAUSE OF THE EXTREME ODOR OF GUN POWER PLUS I DID NOT KNOW WHAT THIS WAS AND I MENTIONED... THE VALUJET INCIDENT.  THEY ALL AGREED AND TURNED THIS OVER TO TO ME AND DID NOT GIVE ME ANY PROBLEM WITH MY DECISION...THE CAPTAIN WAS AGREEABLE AND THE FLIGHT WHICH WAS ALREADY LATE INBOUND (LQB 1 HR..29 MINS.) TOOK A 22 SRS DELAY...FLIGHT 855.28 DEPARTED MEMPHIS AT 2302 FROM B/5.  I CALLED THE LOCAL FBI OFFICE AND INFORMED THEM OF THE INCIDENT (2345) PLUS TO CALL CSM ROGER RIDDLE IN THE A.M. AND HE COULD ARRANGE FOR THEM TO PICK-UP THIS ITEM FOR OUR FILES AND I HAVE MR. PETROUSKY'S BUSINESS CARD.  I LEFT ITEMS FOR CSM ROGER RIDDLE'S HANDLING.  OUR AGENTS WHO DID A VERY COMMENDABLE JOB IN DISCOVERING THIS WERE (UP/GRADE) ESE ALLAN BOCK AND ESE KEN GREGORY..CSM DAVE MOREAU IS GOING TO WRITE LETTERS OF COMMENDATIONS.  THEY SHOULD NOT HAVE HAD THIS ABOARD THE AIRCRAFT AND ESPECIALLY AFTER USING WITH HIGH EXPLOSIVES AND LEAVING SUCH A HIGH ODOR OF SMOKE AND GUN POWDER. ALSO THEY NEVER DECLARED THIS ITEM TO ANY NWA EMPLOYEE...PLUS THE VALUJECT INCIDENT IS FRESH ON OUR

column168: I WAS INTIALLY ADVISED OF A BLOOD SPILL.  I ADVISED THAT WE NEED TO HANDLE IT ACCORDING TO OUR ESTABLISHED BLOOD SPILL PROCEDURES.  WE OPENED THE BOX TO REVEAL A DECAPITATED AND DRAWN & QUARTERED BODY OF A 92 YEAR OLD MAN, IDENTIFIED AS GUSTAV JOHNSON.  HE ALLEDGELY DIED ON 6/19/96.  HE HAD DONATED HIS BODY TO SCIENCE.  FEDEX STRICTLY PROHIBITS THE CARRIAGE OF DISINTERRED REMAINS.  THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN TWO SORT BAGS AND REMOVED FROM THE SORT.  WE PUT 15# OF DRY ICE IN THE BOX TO KEEP THE CONTENTS FROM DETERIORATING ANY FURTHER.  THE SHIPPER ADVISED THAT HE HAD SHIPPED THE BOX WITH 5# OF DRY ICE, YET THE BOX AND AIRBILL DID NOT REFLECT ANY MARKING, LABELING OR OTHER INDICATOR THAT DRY ICE WAS PRESENT.  ON 6/28/96, CHRIS RICHARDS, FEDEX LEGAL WAS NOTIFIED BY THE RECIPIENTS LEGAL DEPT THAT THE REMAINS WERE TESTED POSITIVE FOR HEPITTUS B & HEPITITUS C. AS THE REASON FOR DEATH WAS IDENTIFIED AS PNEUMONIA AND OTHER RELATED CAUSES, WE WERE UNAWARE THAT THE INFECTIOUS SUBSTANCE EXISTED.  DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE CONTENTS, THE RECIPIENT FLEW TO MEMPHIS ON 6/22, REPACKED THE CONTENTS AND HAD STERLING COURIERS TENDER THE FREIGHT TO A PASSENGER AIRLINE FOR TRANSPORT TO EXTON, PA.  FEDEX HAS ADVISED THE SHIPPER & RECIPIENT IN WRITING VIA FAX AND OVERNIGHT LETTER THAT ALL  FUTURE LIKE SHIPMENTS ARE PROHIBITED AND ANY ATTEMPT TO TENDER SUCH SHIPMENTS WILL NOT BE TOLERATED.  I DISCUSSED THE ISSUE WITH A DETECTIVE WRIGHT, TUSCON POLICE DEPT, AS THE SHIPPER LOCATION IS A RESIDENTAL HOME IN TUCSON, A. THEY ARE INVESTIGATING.  I ADVISED TERRY BURGESS, FAA SECURITY, BNA CASFU ON 6/24 & 6/28, 1996.   THIS SHIPMENT IS UNDECLARED.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: DURING THE SORT A STRONG ODOR WAS NOTICED.  THE BOX WAS OPENED TO DETERMINE ORIGIN OF ODOR.  WE FOUND 40 CANS OF HAIR SPRAY AND HAIR COLOR. THE HAIR SPRAY CANS APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN USED & THE HAIR COLORING WAS, I BELIEVE, NON-AEROSOL, THOSE CONTAINERS HAD LOOSE/DEFECTIVE CAPS.  THERE WAS NO APPRECABLE SPILL BUT THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AND THE MATERIAL WAS GIVING OFF A DISCERNABLE AROMA/ODOR.  AS THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATOR TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED, WE DID NOT KNOWINGLY ACCCEPT THESE UNDECLARED COMMODITIES INTO OUR SYSTEM.  WE HAVE ATTEMPTED TO NOTIFY THE SHIPPER SEVERAL TIMES, WITHOUT SUCCESS.  AS THE SHIPPER IS AN AMERICAN AIRLINES EMPLOYEE,, SHIPPING ON HER DISCOUNT, AA SECURITY, DICK DEDGE, HAS BEEN CALLED.  IN ADDITION, RHONDA HATMAKER FROM FAA-LAX-CASFO ALSO HAS BEEN ADVISED.  WE WILL HOLD THE FREIGHT PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.  THIS SHIPMENT IS UNDECLARED.

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS DROPPED AND UPON IMPACT WITH THE CEMENT FLOOR, THE INNER CONTAINER CRACKED AND DUMPED MOST OF IT'S CONTENTS.  WE WERE FAXED THE MSDS WHICH CONFIRMED OUR SUSPICIONS OF UNDECLARED HAZMAT.  THE FAA, BOB WILSON, WAS NOTIFIED AT 1600 PDT.  I LEFT A MESSAGE ON HIS VOICEMAIL AND ORDERED THE FREIGHT HELD FOR AN FAA INSPECTION NEXT WEEK.  IN THE MEANTIME THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED US THAT THE CONTENTS, HUMAN TISSUE WOULD SPOIL IF NOT PRESERVED.  I MADE THE DECISION TO GET THE SEA FEDEX EMPLOYEES TO TAKE PICTURES OF THE BOX & CONTENTS AND GET THE SHIPPER TO PICK  UP THE PACKAGE.  WE TOOK PICTURES & THE SHIPPER RECOVERED THE FREIGHT.  I NOTIFIED BOB WILSON OF MY DECISION ON MONDAY, JUNE 24TH.  HE AGREED THAT WE (I) MADE THE CORRECT DECISION AND THAT HE HAD NO QUALMS WITH THE PREMATURE RELEASE AS LONG AS WE HAD THE EVIDENCE.  PICTURES WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.  THIS SHIPMENT IS UNDECLARED.
