TETRADIS NOTIFIED TO RESPOND TO SCENE. R. SIMONSON DISPATCHED TO PATERSON FACILITY TO PICK UP EMPTY TOTE & OTHER MATERIALS. 2:15 PM - M. DONATIELLO RECEIVED CALL FROM PASSAIC FIRE DEPT. ABOUT SPILL. MD FAXED MSDS TO FIRE CHIEF. PASSAIC FD NOTIFIED MD THAT SPILL WAS RELEASING FROM TRUCK ONTO THE STREET. MD ENACTED BCC EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN. MD INFORMED PASSAIC FD THAT WATER SHOULD BE USED TO DILUTE MATERIAL TO REDUCE HAZARDS. 2:25 PM - CONTACTED PASSAIC COUNTY BOARD OF HEALTH (VANESSA). SHE INDICATED THAT SOMEONE WOULD CALL BACK. NO FURTHER INFORMATION WAS REQUESTED BY VANESSA. NO SPECIFIC SPILL FORM TO FILL OUT. 2:30 PM - D. TETRADIS CALLED FROM SCENE. PASSAIC FD SUITING UP FOR LEVEL A RESPONSE & CONTAINING MATERIAL; NO WATER BEING APPLIED. 2:33 PM - CHRIS SUDOL FROM PASSAIC COUNTY BOH CALLED TO FOLLOW UP ON REPORTED INCIDENT. MD NOTIFIED CHRIS SUDOL THAT WATER SHOULD BE USE TO REDUCE HAZARD. 2:37 PM - NJDEP NOTIFIED BY MD. CASE #96-6-18-1445-13 OPERATOR 9 DETAILS: NO INJURIES, NO EVACUATION, CALL PUT ON HOLD BY DEP UNTIL 2:44 PM. FOLLOWING INFO GIVEN: NAME, COMPANY NAME, PHONE #, LOCATION, TIME OF SPLIT, MATERIAL SPILLED, APPROXIMATE QUANTITY SPILLED, CAUSE OF SPILL: UNKNOWN. ASSISTANCE NOT REQUIRED. 2:55 PM - UPDATE BY D. TETRADIS ON SCENE. 2-3 THREE FIRE TRUCKS, SOME EMERGENCY VEHICLES, PASSAIC COUNTY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE UNIT, PASSAIC POLICE ON SCENE. AWAITING NJDEP, WHO HAD NOT YET RESPONDED. 3:05 PM - WALT JANICEK, NJDEP, CALLED & REQUESTED MSDS FOR PRODUCT, WHICH WAS FAXED TO 201-669-3993. MD AGAIN REQUESTED THAT SPILL BE DILUTED WITH WATER TO REDUCE HAZARD. NJDEP DECIDED TO SENT SOMEONE TO ASSESS SCENE. MD INFORMED W. JANICEK IF A RESPONSE CONTRACTER WAS NEEDED THAT BCC WOULD NOTIFY OUR CONTRACTOR. 3:10 PM - CONTACTED FMC & SPOKE WITH ER PERSONNEL TO GAIN OCCURRENCE THAT DILUTION OF SPILL WITH WATER WAS BEST COURSE OF ACTION. FMC: SHOULD DILUTE TO BELOW 8%. 3:25 PM - CHRIS GIVENS AT SCENE FOR NJDEP. TOTE BIN NOW EMPTY. PASSAIC FD FLOODING AREA WITH WATER TO SEWER. PH BEING MONITORED, SHOWING A LEVEL OF 5. BCC WAS TOLD TO NOTIFY PASSAIC VALLEY SEWER COMMISSION OF SPILL. MD TOLD THAT SITUATION WAS UNDER CONTROL AND THAT PASSAIC FD WOULD CONTINUE TO WASH DOWN AREA & THEN RELEASE TRUCK. 3:30 PM - MD NOTIFIED ANDY CALTAGIRONE (817-5723) OF PVSC. MD INFORMED HIM THAT WE WOULD SEND SHORT NOTE RE:SPILL & PROVIDE PVSC WITH MORE DETAILED REPORT WITHIN A FEW WEEKS. 4:00 PM - DRIVER & TRUCK RELEASED TO COMPLETE DELIVERIES. 5:30 PM - M. WILSON & TRUCK RETURN TO OAKLAND. PRELIMINARY INSPECTION OF TOTE BIN BY MD & DAB DISCOVERED SPLIT AT BOTTOM EDGE OF PE BOTTLE. TOTE LAST DOT TESTED 1/95. 6:15 PM - MD & DAB RECEIVED CALL FROM DPTY. column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2:50 P.M., FLIGHT 325 WAS PREPARING FOR DEPARTURE WHEN A STRONG ODOR WAS NOTICED WHILE THE RAMP SERVICE WAS LOADING BAGGAGE INTO PIT #6 OF AIRCRAFT #786.  PREVIOUSLY, TOOL BOXES TRAVELING AS AIR CARGO HAD BEEN LOADED AS WELL.  THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM ONE OF THEM WHICH WAS LEAKING A BLACK GLUE SUBSTANCE.  ACCORDING TO THE RAMP SUPERVISOR THERE WAS A 3 FT IN DIAMETER SPOT OF THIS SUBSTANCE COVERING THE AIRCRAFT PIT FLOOR BETWEEN PIT #5 & 6.  THE FREIGHT WAS REMOVED IMMEDIATELY AND THE RAMP ATTEMPTED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL BUT IT DRIED INSTANTLY.  THE HAZMAT TEAM WAS THEN CALLED OUT TO DETERMINE IF THE SUBSTANCE WAS HAZARDOUS.  THE AIRCRAFT WAS CHECKED AND TESTS WERE DONE BEFORE THE AIRCRAFT WAS RELEASED. SUBSTANCE WAS DETERMINED TO BE SOME KIND OF GASKET GLUE.  THIS SHIPMENT IS UNDECLARED.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED THAT TANKCAR UTLX 13437 WAS NOTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE CAR WAS SET TO THE RIP TRACK AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  CAR UTLX 13437 ARRIVED YERMO IN THE HKYR-13 AT 1507 HOURS, SUNDAY, JUNE 16, 1966.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE TANK CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT.  THE SAFETY VENT CONSISTED OF A LINED FLANGE ASSEMBLY WITH AN INNER DISC RETAINER, HELD IN PLACE WITH THREE BOLTS/NUTS.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS MOUNTED OUTSIDE THE WORK PLATFORM AREA TOWARDS THE "B" END OF THE CAR.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS DISASSEMBLED AND THE BURST DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 100 POUND BS&B STAINLESS/TEFLON FRANGIBLE DISC.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED, AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS INSPECTED, AND FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES; AND THE SHIPPER FOR INFORMATION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: SPECIALIST CTS RICHARD E TUFTS RECEIVED A PAGE FROM MYO LANCE HARDESTY AT YARD CENTER, DOLTON, IL. AT 1832 HRS ADVISING THAT PIGGYBACK TRAILER REAZ 730285 ON CAR # TTWX 993409 WAS NOTED TO BE LEAKING MATERIAL.  MTO HARDESTY ADVISED THAT TRAILER WAS PLACARDED AS A FLAMMABLE 1993, AND THAT THE SHIPPING PAPERS INDICATED THE LOAD AS 80 DRUMS FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, N.O.S., (CONTAINS ETHYL SILICATE AND ETHYL ALCOHOL).  SPECIALIST TUFTS INITIATED RESPONSE TO SCENE FROM ST. LOUIS AREA AND IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED REGIONAL MANAGER, CTS TOM ROBINSON AND ADVISED OF INCIDENT.  AT 1850 SPECIALIST TUFTS CONTACTED HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL SVCS AND REQUESTED RESPONSE.  CHEMTREC, TOM FLORES WAS CONTACTED BY SPECIALIST TUFTS AT 2100 HRS FOLLOWING RETURN CALLS FROM HERITAGE SPECIALIST TUFTS THEN CONTACTED THE ILLINOIS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY (IEMA) AT 2104 HRS AND OBTAINED SPILL REPORT ID # 961173.  SPECIALIST TUFTS THEN CONTACTED P&FC OFFICER KIRK JACOBSON AND REQUESTED THAT HE RESPOND TO SCENE. ***** AT APPROX. 2315 HRS, SPECIALIST TUFTS MET WITH MR. JACOBSON, HERITAGE CREW, AND AARON, THE ON DUTY MYO AND OPENED THE TRAILER.  HERITAGE CREWS MADE ENTRY AND NOTED TWO BARRELS LEAKING AND DETERMINED THAT LESS THAN 25 GALS HAD BEEN RELEASED.  BARRELS WERE OVERPACKED AND INSPECTION OF THE COMPLETE LOAD MADE.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT APPROX 30 BARRELS WOULD HAVE TO BE OVERPACKED IN ORDER TO COMPLY WITH REGULATIONS DUE TO DAMAGES SUSTAINED. MR. JACOBSEN OBTAINED PHOTOGRAPHS OF THE IMPROPER MANNER IN WHICH THIS LOAD WAS BLOCKED, BRACED AND LOADED.  IT APPEARED THAT AN INEFFECTIVE, IMPROPERLY INSTALLED GATE BRACE HAD BEEN PLACED AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD AT ONE TIME, HOWEVER, IT FAILED DUE TO IMPROPER CONSTRUCTION AND IMPROPER LOADING.  IT WAS NOTED THAT THERE WAS NO BANDING OR WRAPPING OF THE BARRELS ON PALLETS WHICH ALLOWED THE WHOLE LOAD TO SHIFT, EVENTUALLY CAUSING RUPTURE OF THE BARRELS.  IT WAS MR. JACOBSON'S CONTENTION THAT THE LOAD WAS IMPROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED AND THAT THE SHIPPER WOULD BE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE COSTS OF TRANSFER AND CLEANUP.  ADDITIONALLY, SPECIALIST TUFTS FOUND AN ENVELOPE IN THE LOAD THAT HAD BEEN SEALED WITH PACKING TAPE THAT STATED ON ITS EXTERIOR, "SHIPPING PAPERS ENCLOSED".  THE ENVELOPE WAS MARKED TO INDICATE THAT IT CONTAINED CERTIFICATE OF ANALYSIS, PACKING LIST AND MSDS SPECIALIST TUFTS OPENED THIS ENVELOPE TO REVIEW CONTENTS AND FOUND IT TO BE EMPTY, CONTAINING NO INFORMATION.  ALSO, AS INFO, UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, SPECIALIST TUFTS NOTED THE TRAILER WAS IMPROPERLY PLACARDED AS IT WAS DISPLAYING CLASS #3 RESIDUE PLACARDS. SPECIALIST TUFTS PLACED PROPER PLACARDS ON THE TRAILER PRIOR TO MOVING IT TO THE RAMP FOR TRANSFER. ****** 062996 - AT 0800 HRS., CREWS FROM HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL, GT TRANSFER AND SPECIALIST TUFTS BEGAN TRANSFER AND OVERPACK PROCEDURES AT THE DOLTON RAMP FACILITY.  48 NON-DAMAGED 55 GAL DRUMS WERE PLACED IN TRAILER CSXZ 236755 AND PROPERLY BLOCKED/BRACED. 31 DAMAGED/OVERPACKED DRUMS AND 1 NON DAMAGED DRUM WERE RELOADED

column168: WE TRANSPORTED THIS TOTE FROM OUR DALLAS, TEXAS TERMINAL TO OUR ROSEVILLE, MINNESOTA TERMINAL WITH NO PROBLEMS.  PENNER INTERNATIONAL TRUCKING THEN PICKED THIS UP TO TAKE TO THE CONSIGNEE IN NORTH DAKOTA.  THEY RETURNED THIS SAYING THERE WAS A SMALL LEAK COMING FROM THE VALVE.  WE THEN CALLED SUPERIOR SPECIAL SERVICES, 800-688-4005, FOND DU LAC, WHO THEN CONTRACTED BAY WEST INC., ST. PAUL, MINNESOTA.  BAY WEST TRANSFERRED THE PRODUCT TO 55 GALLON DRUMS AND THEN INSPECTED THE VALVE.  THEY FOUND THAT THE MECHANISM INTERNAL TO THE VALVE WAS NOT SEATING PROPERLY.  THIS IMPROPER SEATING APPEARED TO BE THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK TO THE TOTE OF DIESEL FUEL ADDITIVE.  ON JULY 11, 1996, THE MINNESOTA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION WAS AT OUR TERMINAL TO CHECK HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENTS.  THEY ALSO AGREED WITH BAY WEST ABOUT THE MALFUNCTION OF THE VALVE.  WE ARE CURRENTLY DEALING WITH PRIMROSE OIL ON THIS MATTER.

I RESPONDED TO THE LEAKING BOX WEARING PROPER PPE. I USED MY DECISION TREE TO DETERMINE IF THE BOX WAS HAZARDOUS. I REFERRED TO MY CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEETS. I USED SODIUM BICARBONATE UNTIL MATERIAL TESTED BETWEEN 6 AND 9 ON THE PH SCALE. I PROCESSED CONTAMINATED MATERIAL THROUGH THE DMP, AND REPACKED THE GOOD PORTION ACCORDING TO UPS SPECIFICATIONS AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: ON JUNE 20, 1996 A CALL WAS RECEIVED AT OUR DISPATCH FOR A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN BUILDING A. TAMMY FLORENCE. HAZMAT SPILL TECHNICIAN WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP LEAKING SHIPMENT. UPON ARRIVAL TAMMY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX LEAKING A LIQUID. NO MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE BOX TO INDICATE IT WAS HAZARDOUS. TAMMY PROCEEDED TO PH THE SHIPMENT AND WAS AT THIS TIME FOUND TO BE CORROSIVE. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION  THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS OPEN AND DISCOVERED TO CONTAIN THE 1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES OF A COMPOUND CLEANING LIQUID OF WHICH ONE HAD LEAKED APPROX 13 OUNCES. THE INNER PACKAGE WAS IN A SPEC 4G PACKAGE. THE TWO GAL OF CONTAINERS DID NOT HAVE POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE LIDS. NO ABSORBENTS WERE USED. THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE KEPT UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTIL INVESTIGATED.
